(68,'Detailed Cataract','<div><b><i><span>PATIENT INSTRUCTIONS FOLLOWING EYE SURGERY</span></i></b></div>\r\n<div align=\"center\"><b><i>(except for those undergoing trabeculectomy, cataract with trabeculectomy)</i></b></div>\r\n<div align=\"center\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>1.</span>Start drops today as instructed and return tomorrow: (Given to Patient Prior to Surgery)</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>2.Unless otherwise instructed, continue to use all preoperative oral medications and injectable medications such as insulin. If you have been advised to discontinue any medications such as anticoagulants (blood thinners) prior to surgery, you should not resume them until your examination on the first postoperative day is performed, when you will be advised as to whether or not you should restart those types of medication.</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>3.</span>No special precautions are necessary and you may move about normally in your home. You may watch television, bend, and cook, read (including computer reading). However, it is best not to read a great deal on the day of surgery. Beginning on the day after surgery, you may shower and apply make-up, etc.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>4.</span>The vision immediately after eye surgery can be very variable. Some patients notice halos and/or have blurred or cloudy vision for hours or occasionally even several days, and this reaction can be different for each eye. <span>Therefore, you should not be alarmed if you experience this.</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>5.</span>If you have discomfort or aching near your eye, you may take two (2) Tylenol tablets every four (4) hours (not to exceed 12 tablets in a 24 hour period).</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>6.</span>If your eye feels &quot;sandy&quot;, as if something is in it, close both eyes and lie quietly in a darkened room.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>7.</span>As your eye will probably be sensitive to bright light or sunlight, the use of sunglasses is advised.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>8.</span>Some patients might note a red or pink hue to objects after surgery. This usually disappears within 24-48 hours.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>9.</span>If any of the following problems develop, please call the doctor&rsquo;s office that day:</div>\r\n<div><span>a) Increased discomfort or pain in the operated eye</span></div>\r\n<div><span>b) Any worsening of vision in the operated eye</span></div>\r\n<div><span>c) Increased sensitivity to light (greater than at the time of discharge from the Institute)</span></div>\r\n<div><span>d) Any questions concerning your condition.</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>10.<span>Temporary elevation of eye pressure after surgery is very common, and occurs in approximately 10-15% of patients. Although this occurs frequently, it almost never does any harm. (A notable exception is the patient with glaucoma and advanced visual field loss. Further damage could occur in these patients, and special precautions are therefore taken in this situation);</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>The symptoms of sudden pressure elevation are rapid blurring of vision over a relatively short period of time (one hour or so is typical), pain and headache. If you develop these symptoms after returning home following eye surgery, please call our office for instructions. </span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>Do not sit at home wondering whether or not you should call. It is better to call and be safe.</span></div>\r\n<div>Post operative appointment and instructions given to patient.</div>'),
(69,'Chalazion','<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<b><font face=\"Cochin-Bold\" size=\"4\"><font face=\"Cochin-Bold\" size=\"4\">Instructions after Chalazion (Stye) Surgery</font></font></b></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">1) Carefully remove the patch 2 hours after surgery. If the patch seems stuck on the skin, use room</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">temperature bottled water to soak the patch off and to gently clean the eyelids</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">2) After the patch is removed, apply ice compresses to your lid (15 minutes at a time) until bedtime using</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">ice cubes in a ziplock bag, wrapped in a single paper towel. Frozen peas or freezer gel packs are</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">acceptable. Ice helps prevent bruising &amp; swelling of the eyelid, but don&rsquo;t apply ice directly to the skin</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">since it can cause burns.</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">3) The morning after your surgery, start using moist, hot packs. Clean paper towels soaked in hot water are</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">the best source of moist heat. Hot packs will allow the chalazion to drain and are important to keep the</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">chalazion from recurring. Perform hot packs three times a day, 10 minutes each time, for 5 days.</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">4) Apply antibiotic/steroid ointment under the eyelid two times a day.</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"TimesNewRomanMS\">5) </font><font face=\"Cochin\">Tylenol is safest to take for pain. If Tylenol is not adequate, call Dr. Hidaji for a stronger medication.</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<b><font face=\"Cochin-Bold\" size=\"4\"><font face=\"Cochin-Bold\" size=\"4\">Frequently Asked Questions</font></font></b></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<b><font face=\"Cochin-Bold\">Is it normal to have eyelid swelling and bleeding after surgery?</font></b></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">Expect to have swelling, redness, and some bruising after eyelid surgery. It is normal to have some oozing of</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">blood tinged fluid for 1 or 2 days. The swelling will be worst the morning after surgery, and will decrease</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">thereafter. If there is steady bleeding after 24 hours, call Dr. Hidaji.</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<b><font face=\"Cochin-Bold\">When can I shower?</font></b></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">You should keep the eyelids clean and dry after surgery. You can shower with your head held back. Avoid</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">hot water and steam, as these can cause bleeding.</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<b><font face=\"Cochin-Bold\">When can I return to normal activities?</font></b></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">Do not stoop over or lift more than 10 pounds for one week after surgery. Avoid heavy physical exertion for</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">a week after surgery.</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<b><font face=\"Cochin-Bold\">CALL THE OFFICE at 901-754-3937 if you have any questions or if:</font></b></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">Severe eye pain</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">Thick yellow discharge from the incision</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">You can&rsquo;t see out of the eye(s) that had surgery (minor blurring is normal)</font></p>\r\n<p align=\"LEFT\">\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin\">Eyelids start to swell or become red</font></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<font face=\"Cochin-Bold\"><b>Anything </b></font><font face=\"Cochin\">is getting worse - pain, discharge, eyelid swelling, bleeding, vision</font></p>\r\n'),
(70,'Pterygium','<p class=\"paragraph_style_3\" style=\"padding-top: 0pt;\">\r\n	The pterygium has been removed from the surface of the eye.&nbsp; Generally a conjunctival graft is sutured in place.&nbsp; A pad is over the eye and should remain in place until tomorrow.&nbsp; A contact lens may be in the eye.&nbsp; It is normal to experience significant pain in the first 24-48 hours.&nbsp; Please take Panadeine Forte if required.&nbsp; The cornea is a very sensitive area.&nbsp; The pain settles as the cornea heals.&nbsp; Please take your other medications as usual.</p>\r\n<p class=\"paragraph_style_3\">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"paragraph_style_3\">\r\n	The eye pad is removed the next day.&nbsp; The eye is cleaned with cool boiled water or saline.&nbsp; Antibiotic drops are used initially, then steroid drops are added as the cornea heals.&nbsp; The sutures can be scratchy.&nbsp; Please do not rub the eye.</p>\r\n<p class=\"paragraph_style_3\">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"paragraph_style_3\">\r\n	To put in eye drops, wash hands, then, with chin up, look up, pull the lower lid down and allow a drop to fall inside the lower lid.&nbsp; Close the eye for 30 seconds.&nbsp; Gently dab away any excess.&nbsp; Wait 5 minutes before using the next drop.</p>\r\n<p class=\"paragraph_style_3\">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"paragraph_style_3\">\r\n	Keep the eye dry and closed in the shower for the first few days.&nbsp; Do not lift heavy things, garden, play sport, or wet your face swimming for 2-4 weeks.&nbsp; Please wear sunglasses outside.&nbsp; The post operative drops will be gradually reduced over 4-8 weeks.&nbsp; It is recommended to use lubricating drops / gel and sunglasses long term, but particularly in the first 6 months to reduce the risk of recurrence of the pterygium.</p>\r\n'),
(53,'Insertion of Intacs Intra-Corneal Ring','<p style=\"text-align: center\">Post-Operative Instructions for Insertion of Intacs Intra-Corneal Ring</p>\r\n<p>1.Resting the day of surgery is advised.</p>\r\n<p>2. Apply Vigamox &amp; Prednisolone in the operative eye four times a day.&nbsp; Apply Bromday in the operative eye one time a day.&nbsp; Wait 3-5 minutes between each drop.&nbsp; Use these drops for 1 week.</p>\r\n<p>3. DO NOT RUB YOUR EYE&nbsp; as this may lead to improper healing of the incision.</p>\r\n<p>4. Wear the proctective shield at night for one week.</p>\r\n<p>5. Foreign body sensations, or &quot;scracthiness&quot;, light sensitivity and glare are common during the immediate recovery period.</p>\r\n<p>6. Pain is not expected. Should you experience pain, please call the office.&nbsp; If it is after hours, call ReVision and leave a detailed message with the night operator.&nbsp; Dr. Schumer will be notified and will call you back.</p>\r\n<p>7. You may experience dryness following your surgery.&nbsp; We recommend a preservative-free artificial tear to lubricate your eyes.</p>\r\n<p>8. You should expect your vision to fluctuate during the first 3-4 weeks post-op recovery period.</p>\r\n<p>9. Avoid make-up, lotions and after-shave for 2 days after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>10. You may wash your face or shower, but avoid rubbing across your eyes for one week after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>11. No swimming for one week after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>12. You may resume other exercise routines the next day; eye protection is recommended.</p>\r\n<p>13. Cigarette/cigar smoke will irrate the eye and can affect healing and should be avoided for one week after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>Your first follow-up exam is scheduled at {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} in the {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} office.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>\r\n<p>Columbus Office: (614)781-0499 or (800)475-2113</p>\r\n<p>Mansfield Office: (419)525-3737 or (800)775-3937</p>'),
(54,'Minor Post-Operative Inst. Sheet','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>MINOR POST-OPERATIVE INSTRUCTION SHEET</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>DURING THE FIRST 24 HOURS AFTER SURGERY:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. Your eye may tear.&nbsp; Gently dry the tears.&nbsp; <strong>DO NOT RUB </strong>your eye.</p>\r\n<p>2. Resume your normal routine.&nbsp; You may bend or stoop to do things such as tying your shoes or picking up a newspaper.</p>\r\n<p>3. You may watch television or read.</p>\r\n<p>4. Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving.</p>\r\n<p>5. Resume your regular medications.</p>\r\n<p>6. Whether you are inside or outside, you may be light-sensitive.&nbsp; You have been provided with sunglasses; wear them for eye comfort.</p>\r\n<p>7. Your next appointment will be scheduled or confirmed as you leave the office with each visit.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EYE DROPS:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>{TEXTBOX_LARGE}</strong></p>\r\n<p>Wash hands thoroughly before starting.&nbsp; Instill eye drop inside lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes.&nbsp; To avoid placing pressure on the eye, pull down the lower lid with your finger on the skin just below the lower lid and place the drop in the lower lid.</p>\r\n<p><strong>MEDICATION:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>{TEXTBOX_LARGE}</strong></p>\r\n<p>I certify that I have read (or have had read to me) and full understand the above post-operative instructions.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(55,'Superficial Keratectomy Post Op Inst.','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>SURPERFICIAL KERATECTOMY</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>GOING HOME INSTRUCTIONS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>D. JAMES SCHUMER</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>614-781-0499 OR 800-475-2113</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>What to expect with your eye:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>1. Some redness, light sensitivity and tearing are normal following your surgery. You may experience a scratchy sensation leading to discomfort in your eye after your surgery.&nbsp; You can take the pills as ordered and if this is insufficient, you should call the office.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>2. A cold compress is soothing and beneficial to the eye. DO NOT RUB YOUR EYE.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Activity:</p>\r\n<p>1. Light physical activity is permitted and encouraged.&nbsp; You may read or watch TV.&nbsp; You may walk outside, ride in a care, train, plane or bus.&nbsp; Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving. You may shower bathe, shampoo your hair, or visit your hairdresser. Avoid getting soap in your eye.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>2.&nbsp;Avoid bumping or rubbing the operated eye.&nbsp; You may bend or stoop to do things such as picking up the newspaper and tying your shoe.</p>\r\n<p>3. You may notice some increased ssensitivity to light. Sunglasses may be helpful; wear them as needed.</p>\r\n<p>Eye Drops:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">Eye Drops are necessary following surgery to promote healing, provide comfort, and prevent infection.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>TOBRADEX- ONE DROP IN OPERATED EYE 4 TIMES A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">Medication:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>VICODIN- ONE TABLET EVERY 4 HOURS AS NEEDED FOR PAIN.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Follow-Up Care:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">Your next appointment will be scheduled by the receptionist for 3 days after your surgery.</p>\r\n<p>I understand these instructions and have a copy: {TEXTBOX_LARGE}</p>\r\n<p>*****If you have any questions or feel that something is unusual, do not hesitate to call Dr. Schumer at (614)781-0499 or toll free at (800)475-2113.******</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>'),
(56,'Visian ICL Surgery Post Op Inst. #1','<p style=\"text-align: center\">Visian ICL Surgery</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">POST-OPERATIVE INSTRUCTION SHEET</p>\r\n<p>1. Your eye may tear. Gently dry the tears. DO NOT RUB your eye.</p>\r\n<p>2. You may take one or two Extra-Strength Tylenol every four hours for pain, only if necessary. A warm compress is also soothing and beneficial to the eye. If this is insufficient, please call the office.</p>\r\n<p>3. Resume your normal routine. You may bend or stoop to do things such a tying your shoes or picking up a newspaper.</p>\r\n<p>4. You may watch television or read.</p>\r\n<p>5. No eye make-up for 3 days.</p>\r\n<p>6. No swimming for 1 week.</p>\r\n<p>7. Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving.</p>\r\n<p>8. Resume your regular medications.</p>\r\n<p>9. Whether you are inside or outside, you may be light-sensitive. You have been provided with sunglasses; wear them for eye comfort.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EYE DROPS: starting today when you get home:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>1. Prednisolone- one drop in operated eye 4 times a day.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>2. Vigamox- one drop in operated eye 3 times a day.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>3. Bromday- one drop in operated eye once a day.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Wait a few minutes between drops.&nbsp; Wash hands thoroughly before starting. Instill eye drops inside the lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes. To avoid placing pressure on the eye, pull down the lower lid with your finger on the skin just below the lower lid and place the drops in the lower lid.</p>\r\n<p>Best wishes for speedy recovery.&nbsp; Please call our office if you have any questions.&nbsp; We look forwad to seeing you tomorrow.</p>\r\n<p>I certify that I have read (or have had read to me) and fully understand the above post-operative instructions.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>Date: {DATE}</p>\r\n<p>Next Appointment: {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM}</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(57,'Yag Laser Vit Post Op Inst.','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Yag Laser Vitreolysis</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Going Home Instructions</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>D. James Schumer, MD</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>614-781-0499</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>888-475-2113 (toll free)</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>Activity:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>1. You have no restrictions when you leave the facility and can resume&nbsp;your normal activities.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Eye Drops:</p>\r\n<p>1. Begin using:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">-Prednisolone- one drop in operative eye 4 times a&nbsp;day for one week after the laser procedure.</p>\r\n<p>Follow Up Appointment: {TEXTBOX_LARGE}</p>\r\n<p>I understand these instructions and have been given a copy:</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{Nurse\'s Signature}&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>'),
(66,'Pain Management Post Op','<p>Procedure was done without complications. Patient was transferred to recovery in stable condition. Please see op report in scanned images section of this EMR.</p>'),
(58,'Yag Laser Capsulotomy Post Op Inst','<p style=\"text-align: center\">Yag Laser Capsulotomy</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">Going Home Instructions</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">D. James Schumer, MD</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">614-781-0499</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">888-475-2113 (toll free)</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"> Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">What to expect:</p>\r\n<p>1. You may experience floaters following the procedure.</p>\r\n<p>Activity:</p>\r\n<p>1. You have no restrictions when you leave the facility and can resume your normal activities.</p>\r\n<p>Eye Drops:</p>\r\n<p>1. Begin Using:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">-&nbsp;Prednisolone- one drop in operative eye 4 times a day until your follow up appointment.</p>\r\n<p>Follow up Appointment: {TEXTBOX_LARGE}.</p>\r\n<p>I understand these instructions and have been given a copy:</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(59,'Yag Laser Peripherial Iridotomy Post Op Inst.','<p style=\"text-align: center\">Yag Laser Peripheral Iridotomy</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">Going Home Instructions</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">D. James Schumer, MD</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">614-781-0499</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">888-475-2113 (toll free)</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">What to expect:</p>\r\n<p>1. Drops were used to constrict your pupil for the laser procedure.&nbsp; The pupil may remain constricted for a few hours afterwards.&nbsp; These drops can also cause a headache or an ache above your eyebrow.</p>\r\n<p>2. You can take whatever you normally take for discomfort should you experience any.&nbsp; If this is insufficient, you should call the office.</p>\r\n<p>3. You can resume contact lens wear.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Activity:</p>\r\n<p>1. You have no restrictions when you leave the facility and can resume your normal activities.</p>\r\n<p>Eye Drops:</p>\r\n<p>1. Begin using:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left; margin-left: 40px\">Prednisolone- one drop, 4 times per day in operative eye for 1 week after the laser procedure.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Follow Up Appointment: {TEXTBOX_LARGE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">I understand these instructions and have been given a copy:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(60,'Verisyse Surgery Post Op Inst.','<p style=\"text-align: center\">Verisyse Surgery</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">Going Home Instructions</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">D. James Schumer, MD</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">614-781-0499</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">888-475-2113 (toll free)</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Dr. Schumer will place and eye shield over your eye before leaving the surgery center to protect your eye.&nbsp; If it only necessary to wear the patch this night of your surgery.&nbsp; You may remove it when you wake up in the morning.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>What to expect:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. Some redness, light sensitivity and tearing are normal following your surgery.&nbsp; You may experience a scratchy sensation in your eye after your surgery.&nbsp; The discomfort following this procedure usually requires no more than Tylenol or other non-aspirin products for relief.&nbsp; If this is insufficient, you should call the office.</p>\r\n<p>2. You may have some mattering following your surgery.&nbsp; Moisten a clean washcloth with warm water, wring and gently wipe the eyelid.&nbsp; A warm compress is soothing and beneficial to the eye.&nbsp; <strong>DO NOT RUB YOUR EYE.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Activity:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. Light physicial activity is permitted and encouraged.&nbsp; You may read or watch TV.&nbsp; You may walk outside, ride in a car, train, plane or bus.&nbsp; Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving.&nbsp; You may shower or bathe, shampoo your hair, or visit your hairdresser.&nbsp; Avoid getting soap in your eye.</p>\r\n<p>2. Avoid bumping or rubbing your eye.&nbsp; You may bend or stoop to do things such as picking up the newspaper and tying your shoe.</p>\r\n<p>3. You may notice some increased sensitivity to light. Sunglasses may be helpful; wear them as needed.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Eye Drops:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. Eye drops are necessary following surgery to promote healing, provide comfort, and prevent infection.</p>\r\n<p>2. You may remove the shield to instill the drops the day of surgery, and replace the shield after using the drops.&nbsp; Begin your eye drops as follows:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -Prednisolone- one drop in operative eye 4 times a day.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -Xibrom- one drop in operative eye 1 time a day.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -Vigamox- one drop in operative eye 4 times a day.</p>\r\n<p>3. Wait approximately a few minutes between drops.</p>\r\n<p>4. Wash hands thoroughly before starting.&nbsp; Instill eye drops inside the lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes.&nbsp; It</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">is not necessary to place the drop directly on the eye.&nbsp; To avoid placing pressure on the eye, pull down the lower lid</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">with your finger on the skin just below the lower lid and apply the drop in the lower lid.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Follow-Up Care:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Your next appointment will be scheduled or confirmed as you leave the office each visit.</p>\r\n<p>I understand these instructions and have been given a copy:</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(67,'Retina Post Op Inst.','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div align=\"center\"><b><font size=\"3\">RETINAL SURGERY DISCHARGE INSTRUCTIONS</font></b></div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">You may receive specific instructions from your doctor that conflicts with this sheet. If so, please follow the instructions given by your doctor. </font></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">POST-OPERATIVE MEDICATIONS:</font></div>\r\n<ol type=\"1\">\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Please continue all of your regular systemic medications.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">If you were on eye drops in your non-operative eye, please continue them.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Please use the following drops.</font></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">{TEXTBOX_SMALL} right left both eye {TEXTBOX_SMALL}times a day</font></div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">{TEXTBOX_SMALL} right left both eye {TEXTBOX_SMALL} times a day</font></div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">{TEXTBOX_SMALL} right left both eye {TEXTBOX_SMALL} times a day</font></div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">{TEXTBOX_SMALL} right left both eye {TEXTBOX_SMALL} times a day</font></div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">{TEXTBOX_SMALL} right left both eye {TEXTBOX_SMALL} times a day</font></div>\r\n<ol type=\"1\" start=\"4\">\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Please use the following pills:</font></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">{TEXTBOX_SMALL} {TEXTBOX_SMALL}pill (s) by mouth {TEXTBOX_SMALL}times a day</font></div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">{TEXTBOX_SMALL} {TEXTBOX_SMALL}pill (s) by mouth {TEXTBOX_SMALL}times a day</font></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">SPECIAL INSTRUCTIONS:</font></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<ol type=\"1\">\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Use the eye drops as directed. To instill eye drops, look up and pull the lower lid down gently with one finger on the cheek-then put one drop in the pocket between the lower lid and the eyeball.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">When using eye drops, four times a day means: breakfast, lunch, dinner, bedtime. Two times a day means: upon awakening and at bedtime. You do not have to wake up in the middle of the night to use the drops unless specifically instructed.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">If you run out of the drops-they are usually refillable. If you have any trouble getting a refill, call 617-636-4600.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">When several drops are scheduled to be used at the same time allow a few minutes in between each drop to be used. Use the eye drops in order listed. If any of the medications is an eye ointment (salve) use this last.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Regular or Extra-Strength Tylenol is usually sufficient for any postoperative pain. Aspirin should not be used unless directed by your physician.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">You should clean the eyelids and lashes when discharge builds up, especially in the morning. Use clean cotton balls with warm water or saline eye wash (available in any pharmacy). Looks up and brush down lower lashers, then look down and brush up the upper lashes. This should be done gently.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">After the first night following surgery, you do not need to wear the gauze patch. During the day, wear your prescription glasses or sunglasses if you have them. For the first week, at night, put the metal eye shield over the operated eye. If you do not have prescription glasses or no sunglasses, then wear the shield during the day as well.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">No contact lenses until cleared by your doctor.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">If there is a lot of eyelid swelling, you may use and icepack for 30 minutes, 3 to 4 times a day over the gauze pad.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Follow up care is important. Please call 617-636-4600 to make an appointment for your post operative visit according to your doctor&rsquo;s instruction. </font></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">DO&rsquo;S AND DON&rsquo;TS: </font></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<ol type=\"1\">\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">If you were instructed to stay in a specific position after your surgery (such as face down or right side down), try to maintain this position as much as possible at home. If you were instructed to maintain face down-avoid lying on your back at any time. </font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">If your doctor used an air or gas bubble to reattach your retina then you cannot fly in an airplane until the bubble is gone. (If this applies to you, your doctor will give you further instructions regarding you ability to fly).</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">At home, you should get up and walk around at least several times a day to stimulate circulation in your legs. If you have difficulty with circulation in your legs or a history of blood clots, you should wear TED stockings, which can be purchased in most pharmacies </font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">You may bend down gently after surgery, but no strenuous activity or exercise until we clear you. (Usually 4 weeks following surgery). No lifting over 20 pounds.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">You may wash your hair, shower, shave, etc., after surgery, but be sure to keep your eyes closed and dry them immediately after washing. Do not allow water to get into your eye.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Avoid any jarring or jostling of your head.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Reading and watching T.V. and non-strenuous activities are permitted after surgery. </font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Do not rub the operated eye, or put and pressure on the eye or eyelids.</font></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">COMMON POSTOPERATIVE SYMPTOMS:</font></div>\r\n<div><font size=\"3\">The following symptoms are common after retinal surgery and you should not be concerned if you experience them.</font></div>\r\n<ol type=\"1\">\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Flashing lights.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Persistent floaters, specks or strands in your vision. </font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Mild postoperative pain relived by Tylenol.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Tearing, watery discharge, or a small amount of bloody discharge.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Mild redness and itching of the operated eye.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">A foreign body feeling, like something in the eye. This is usually due to the small dissolvable stitches on the surface of the eye</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Mild bruising, swelling, or drooping of the eyelids. Your lids may not seem to open completely for some time after the surgery.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Dilated pupil. The pupil will usually be large or dilated after surgery. This is usually due to an eye drop we use to relax the papillary muscles.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Double vision.</font></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><b><font size=\"3\">CALL IMMEDIATELY IF THE FOLLOWING SYMPTOMS OCCUR:</font></b></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<ol type=\"1\">\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">The vision was improving and it suddenly decreases.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Severe, increasing pain in the eye.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Persistent nausea and/or vomiting.</font></li>\r\n    <li><font size=\"3\">Thick, pus-like discharge from the eye.</font></li>\r\n</ol>'),
(61,'DSEK Surgery or Reposition Graft Post Op Inst.','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>DSEK Surgery or Reposition Graft</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>YOU WILL HAVE AN EYE SHEILD ON YOUR EYE AFTER SURGERY: (do not remove the patch the day of surgery except to use your eye drops.)</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><strong>RESTRICTION:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. No lifting over 20 pound.</p>\r\n<p>2. No bending with your head below your waist.</p>\r\n<p>3. No straining or strenuous activity.</p>\r\n<p>4. NEVER RUB OR PUSH ON YOUR EYE.</p>\r\n<p>5. Do not get water in your eye.</p>\r\n<p>6. Wear eye shield while sleeping.</p>\r\n<p>7. Wear glasses or tinted eye shield while awake.</p>\r\n<p><strong>CALL THE OFFICE IMMEDIATELY IF:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. You have severe pain that is uncontrolled by your medication(s).</p>\r\n<p>2. Your vision becomes worse.</p>\r\n<p>3. If the redness of your eye worsens.</p>\r\n<p>4. If your lids become swollen.</p>\r\n<p>5. If you experience flashes of light or an increase in floaters.</p>\r\n<p>6. If you have a curtain or cobweb in your vision.</p>\r\n<p><strong>SUNGLASSES:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">You may notice some increased sensitivity to light.&nbsp; Sunglasses may be helpful; wear them as needed.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EYE DROPS:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Eye drops are necessary following surgery to promote healing, prvide comfort, and prevent infection.&nbsp; Follow the instructions below to avoid placing pressure directly on the eye when these drops are instilled.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\"><strong>VIGAMOX- 1 DROP IN OPERATIVE EYE 3 TIMES A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\"><strong>PREDNISOLONE- 1 DROP IN OPERATIVE EYE 4 TIMES A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\"><strong>BROMDAY- 1 DROP IN OPERATIVE EYE ONE TIME A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">Instillation of drops:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">Wash hand thoroughly.&nbsp; Instill eye drops inside the lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes.&nbsp; It is not necessary to place the drop directly on the eye.&nbsp; Pull down the lower lid and apply the drop in the lower lid.</p>\r\n<p>YOUR RESTRICTIONS WILL BE LIFTED AS YOU HEAL.</p>\r\n<p>Your next appointment will be scheduled or confirmed as you leave the office with each visit.</p>\r\n<p>IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS OR FEEL THAT SOMETHING IS UNUSUAL, DO NOT HESITATE TO CALL DR. SCHUMER AT (614)781-0499 OR TOLL FREE (800)475-2113.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>Date: {DATE}</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),
(62,'Cataract or Lensectomy Sx (IOK) Post Op Inst.','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n	<strong>POST-OPERATIVE INSTRUCTION SHEET</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n	<strong>Cataract or Lensectomy Surgery (IOK)</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	<strong>DURING THE FIRST 24 HOURS AFTER SURGERY:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	1. Your eye may tear.&nbsp; Gently dry the tears. DO NOT RUB your eye.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2. You may take one or two Extra-Strength Tylenol every four hours for pain, only if necessary.&nbsp; A warm compress is also soothing and beneficial to the eye.&nbsp; If this is unsufficient, please call the office.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3. Resume your normal routine.&nbsp; You may bend or stoop to do things such as tying your shoes or picking up a newspaper.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	4. You may watch television or read.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	5. Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	6. Resume your regular medications.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	7. Whether you are inside or outside, you may be light-sensitive.&nbsp; You have been provided with sunglasses; wear them for eye comfort.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	8. Your next appointment will be scheduled or confirmed as you leave the office with each visit.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	9. No swimming or hot tub for 1 week following surgery.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>EYE DROPS- starting today when you get home;</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<strong>Vigamox- one drop in operative eye 3 times a day for 4 days.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<strong>Bromday-one drop in operative eye 1 time a day for one month.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<strong>Wash hands thoroughly before starting.&nbsp; Instill eye drop inside lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes.&nbsp; To avoid placing pressure on the eye, pull down the lower lid with your finger on the skin just below the lower lid and place the drop in the lower lid.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<strong>Best wished for a speedy recovery.&nbsp; Please call our office if you have any questions.&nbsp; We look forward to seeing you tomorrow.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<strong>I certify that I have read (or have had read to me) and fully understand the above post-operative instructions.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<strong>{SIGNATURE}</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<strong>Patient&#39;s Signature</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<strong>Date: {DATE}</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	{Nurse&#39;s Signature}</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),
(63,'Visian ICL Surgery Post Op Inst. #2','<p style=\"text-align: center\">Visian ICL Surgery</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">POST-OPERATIVE INSTRUCTION SHEET</p>\r\n<p>1. Your eye may tear. Gently dry the tears. DO NOT RUB your eye.</p>\r\n<p>2. You may take one or two Extra-Strength Tylenol every four hours for pain, only if necessary. A warm compress is also soothing and beneficial to the eye. If this is insufficient, please call the office.</p>\r\n<p>3. Resume your normal routine. You may bend or stoop to do things such a tying your shoes or picking up a newspaper.</p>\r\n<p>4. You may watch television or read.</p>\r\n<p>5. No eye make-up for 3 days.</p>\r\n<p>6. No swimming for 1 week.</p>\r\n<p>7. Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving.</p>\r\n<p>8. Resume your regular medications.</p>\r\n<p>9. Whether you are inside or outside, you may be light-sensitive. You have been provided with sunglasses; wear them for eye comfort.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EYE DROPS: starting today when you get home:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>1. Prednisolone Acetate- one drop in operated eye 4 times a day.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>2. Vigamox- one drop in operated eye&nbsp;1 time a day.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>3. Bromday- one drop in operated eye&nbsp;3 times&nbsp;a day.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Wait a few minutes between drops. Wash hands thoroughly before starting. Instill eye drops inside the lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes. To avoid placing pressure on the eye, pull down the lower lid with your finger on the skin just below the lower lid and place the drops in the lower lid.</p>\r\n<p>Best wishes for speedy recovery. Please call our office if you have any questions. We look forwad to seeing you tomorrow.</p>\r\n<p>I certify that I have read (or have had read to me) and fully understand the above post-operative instructions.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>Date: {DATE}</p>\r\n<p>Next Appointment: {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM}</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(64,'Phakic Lens Post Op Inst. ','<p style=\"text-align: center\">Phakic Lens Post-Operative Instructions</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><u><strong>AFTER YOUR SURGERY:</strong></u></p>\r\n<p>-Some redness, light sensitivity and tearing are normal following your lens implant surgery.&nbsp; You may experience a scratchy sensation in your eye after surgery.&nbsp; The discomfort following lens implant surgery usually requires no more than Tylenol or other non-aspirin products for relief.&nbsp; If this is insufficient, you should call the office.</p>\r\n<p>-An eye shield will need to be worn the day of and first night of your surgery.&nbsp; Remove the eye patch the next morning.&nbsp; Eye shield should be worn at bedtime for 4 additional nights.</p>\r\n<p>-You may have some mattering following your lens implant surgery.&nbsp; Moisten a clean washcloth with warm tap water, wring and gently wipe with the washcloth to cleanse the eye.&nbsp; <strong>DO NOT RUB YOUR EYE.</strong></p>\r\n<p>-Light physical activity is permitted and encouraged.&nbsp; You may read or watch TV.&nbsp; You may walk outside, ride in a care, plane or bus.&nbsp; Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving.&nbsp; You may shower or bathe, shampoo your hair, or visit your hairdresser.&nbsp; Avoid getting soap in your eye.</p>\r\n<p>-Avoid bumping or rubbing the operated eye.&nbsp; You may bend or stoop to do things such as picking up the paper and tying your shoes.</p>\r\n<p>-You may notice some increased sensitivity to light.&nbsp; Sunglasses may be helpful; wear them as needed.</p>\r\n<p>-Eye drops are necessary following surgery to promote healing, provide comfort, and prevent infection.&nbsp; Detailed instructions will be given on your surgery day regarding post operative medication drops.</p>\r\n<p>*<strong>Wait approimately a few minutes between drops.&nbsp; Wash hands thoroughly before starting.&nbsp; Instill eye drops inside the lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes.&nbsp; It is not necessary to place the drop directly on the eye.&nbsp; To avoid placing pressure on the eye pull down the lower lid with your finger on the skin just below the lower lid and apply the drop in the lower lid.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>{SIGNATURE}</strong></p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(65,'Lasik Post Op Inst. ','<p style=\"text-align: center\">Post Operative Instructions Following Lasik Surgery</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Resting/Napping the day of surgery is advised.&nbsp; You will most comfortable with your eyes closed for the first few hours after surgery.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">TobraDex: (antibiotic drop) one drop in the operative eye(s) four times daily for 7 days.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Prednisolone: one drop in operative eye(s) four times daily for 7 days. <strong>DO NOT RUB EYES..No swimming for one week after Lasik surgery.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The protective shield or goggles are to be worn full-time the day of surgery, then at night or when sleeping for four additional night after surgery.&nbsp; You may experience some or all of the following: Foreign body sensation or scratchiness, burning, excessive tearing, light sensitivity glare and halos.&nbsp; These are all considered normal following Lasik surgery.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pain is not expected, should you experience pain please call the office. If after hours, call our office and the answering service will take a message and have Dr. Schumer call you back.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">You may experience dryness following surgery.&nbsp; Dryness can cause fluctuating vision, hazy vision, foreign body sensations, burning and tearing. Use a <strong>preservative free </strong>artificial tear to lubricate your eyes beginning the day after surgery.&nbsp; These drops should be used throughout the day during the first month after surgery.&nbsp; Even if you are not experiencing dryness symptons we encourage using the artificial tears.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Avoid make-ups, lotions, scented sprays, perfume, cologne and after shave for three days after surgery.&nbsp; You may wash your face and shower the next day.&nbsp; Use caution around the eyes.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">You may resume your exercise routine after your one day exam.&nbsp;&nbsp;Eye protection is recommended.&nbsp; Cigarette-cigar smoke may irritate the eye following surgery and should be avoided for five days.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Your first follow up appointment is scheduled @ {TEXTBOX_LARGE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">Mansfield Office: 419-525-3737&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Columbus Office: 614-781-0499</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>'),
(51,'EPI-Lasek-PRK Post Op Inst.','<p>Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITITAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p>DO NOT RUB YOUR EYE. Take your prescription pain medication with some food every 4-6 hrs. As needed for pain. Do not drive or drink alcohol when taking the drugs.</p>\r\n<p>Your bandage contact lens needs to stay in place for 3 days and nights. You may experience varying degrees of discomfort or pain.</p>\r\n<p>If your Bandage Contact Lens comes out do not attempt to replace it. Do the following:</p>\r\n<p>1. Expect increased pain. Take your prescription pain medication and rest with your eyes closed. An ice pack may help to relieve pain, 10min. on, 10min off.</p>\r\n<p>2. Call the office. After hours; call ReVision (phone numbers below); push &quot;0&quot;, leave a message with the night operator and a doctor will be notified.</p>\r\n<p>TobraDex (antibiotic drop): One drop in the operative eye(s) four times daily for one week after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>You may use Voltaren Ophthalmic drops is experiencing pain. Do not use Voltaren unless you are experiencing pain. Discontinue Voltaren drops if it does not help relieve pain.</p>\r\n<p>The protective eye shield or goggles are to be worn full-time the day of surgery, then only at night or when sleeping for 5 nights after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>Foreign body sensations, or &quot;scratchiness,&quot; light sensitivity, glare, halos, excessive tearing, burning are common. Your vision will be blured, hazy &amp; fluctuate.</p>\r\n<p>You may experience dryness following your surgery. Use a preservation-free artificial tear to lubricate your eyes beginning the day after your surgery. These drops should be used throughout the day during the first month after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>Avoid make-up, lotions, and after-shave for 3 days after surgery. You may wash your face or shower but avoid rubbing across your eyes.</p>\r\n<p>No swimming for one week after your surgery. You may resume your exercise routine after your one-day exam; eye protection is recommended.</p>\r\n<p>Cigarette/Cigar smoke may irritate the eye following surgery and should be avoided for 5 days after.</p>\r\n<p>Your first follow-up exam is scheduled at {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} in {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} office.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>\r\n<p>Columbus Office: (614)781-0499 or 1-800-475-2113</p>\r\n<p>Mansfield Office: (614)781-0499</p>'),
(52,'Removal of Intacs Intra-corneal Ring','<p>Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITITAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p>Resting the day of surgery is advised.</p>\r\n<p>Apply TobraDex (antibiotic drop): One drop in the operative eye(s) four times daily for {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM}</p>\r\n<p>DO NOT RUB YOUR EYE. Take your prescription pain medication with some food every 4-6 hrs. As needed for pain. Do not drive or drink alcohol when taking the drugs.</p>\r\n<p>Wear the protective shield(s) at night for one week.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Pain is not expected.&nbsp; </strong>Should you experience pain, please call the office.&nbsp; If it is after hours, call ReVision and push &quot;)&quot; and leave a detailed message with the night operator.&nbsp; The doctor will be notified and call you back.</p>\r\n<p>Foreign body sensations, or &quot;scratchiness,&quot; light sensitivity, glare, halos, excessive tearing, burning are common. Your vision will be blured, hazy &amp; fluctuate.</p>\r\n<p>You may experience dryness following your surgery. Use a preservation-free artificial tear to lubricate your eyes beginning the day after your surgery. These drops should be used throughout the day during the first month after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>Your vision may fluctuate the first several weeks of your recovery period.</p>\r\n<p>Avoid make-up, lotions, and after-shave for 3 days after surgery. You may wash your face or shower but avoid rubbing across your eyes.</p>\r\n<p>No swimming for one week after your surgery.</p>\r\n<p>You may resume your exercise routines the next day; eye protection is recommended.</p>\r\n<p>Cigarette/Cigar smoke may irritate the eye following surgery and should be avoided for 5 days after.</p>\r\n<p>Your first follow-up exam is scheduled at {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} in {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} office.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>\r\n<p>Columbus Office: (614)781-0499 or 1-800-475-2113</p>\r\n<p>Mansfield Office: (614)781-0499</p>'),
(47,'DSEK Surgery of Reposition Graft','<p><strong>YOU WILL HAVE AN EYE SHIELD ON YOUR EYE AFTER SURGERY:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Do not remove the patch the day of surgery except to use your eye drops.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>RESTRICTIONS:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. No lifting over 20 pounds.</p>\r\n<p>2. No bending with your head below your waist.</p>\r\n<p>3. No straining or strenuous activity.</p>\r\n<p>4. NEVER RUB OR PUSH ON YOUR EYE.</p>\r\n<p>5. Do not get water in your eye.</p>\r\n<p>6. Wear eye shield while sleeping.</p>\r\n<p>7. Wear glasses or tinted eye shields while awake.</p>\r\n<p><strong>CALL THE OFFICE IMMEDIATELY IF:</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. You have severe pain that is uncontrolled by your medication(s).</p>\r\n<p>2. Your vision becomes worse.</p>\r\n<p>3. If the redness of your eye worsens.</p>\r\n<p>4. If your lids become swollen.</p>\r\n<p>5. If you experience flashes of light or an increase in floaters.</p>\r\n<p>6. If you have a curtain or cobweb in your vision.</p>\r\n<p><strong>SUNGLASSES:</strong></p>\r\n<p>You may notice some increased sensitivity to light.&nbsp; Sunglasses may be helful; wear them as needed.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EYE DROPS:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Eye Drops are necessary following surgery to promote healing, provide comfort, and prevent infection.&nbsp; Follow the instructions below to avoid placing pressure directly on the eye when these drops are instilled.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\"><strong>VIGAMOX- 1 DROP IN OPERATIVE EYE 3 TIMES&nbsp;A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\"><strong>PREDNISOLONE- 1 DROP IN OPERATIVE EYE 4 TIMES A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\"><strong>BROMDAY- 1 DROP IN OPERATIVE EYE ONE TIME A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">Instillation of drops:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wash hands thoroughly.&nbsp; Instill eye drops inside the lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes.&nbsp; It is not necessary to place the drop directly on the eye.&nbsp; Pull down the lower lid and apply the drop in the lower lid.</p>\r\n<p>YOUR RESTRICTIONS WILL BE LIFTED AS YOU HEAL.</p>\r\n<p>Your next appointment will be scheduled or confirmed as you leave the office with each visit.</p>\r\n<p><strong>IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS OR FEEL THAT SOMETHING IS UNUSUAL, DO NOT HESITATE TO CALL DR. SCHUMER AT (614)781-0499 OR TOLL FREE (800)475-2113.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>{</strong>SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(48,'Post Op Inst. ECP Sx','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>POST OPERATIVE INSTRUCTIONS SHEET </strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>ECP Surgery</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><u><strong>Check GTTS with DJS-Prior to Printing/using</strong></u></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">DURING THE FIRST 24 HOURS AFTER SURGERY:</p>\r\n<p>1. Your eye may tear.&nbsp; Gently dry the tears. DO NOT RUB your eye.</p>\r\n<p>2. You may take one or two Extra-Strength Tylenol every four hours for pain, only if necessary.&nbsp; A warm compress is also soothing and beneficial to the eye.&nbsp; If this is insufficient, please call the office.</p>\r\n<p>3. Resume your normal routine.&nbsp; You may bend or stoop to do things such a tying your shoes or picking up a newspaper.</p>\r\n<p>4. You may watch television or read.</p>\r\n<p>5. Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving.</p>\r\n<p>6. Resume your regular medications.</p>\r\n<p>7. Whether you are inside or outside, you may be light-sensitive.&nbsp; You have been provided with sunglasses; wear them for eye comfort.</p>\r\n<p>8. Your next appointment will be scheduled or confirmed as you leave the office with each visit.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EYE DROPS: starting today when you get home:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Vigamox-one drop in operative eye 2 times per day. <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">check with DJS</span></p>\r\n<p>Prednisolone-one drop in operative ey 4 times per day. <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">check with DJS</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Continue the following glaucoma medications:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Wash hands thoroughly before starting.&nbsp; Instill eye drop inside lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes.&nbsp; To avoid placing pressure on the eye, pull down the lower lid with your finger on the skin just below the lower lid and place the drop in the lower lid.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Best wished for a speedy recovery.&nbsp; Please call our office if you have any questions.&nbsp; We look forward to seeing you tomorrow.</p>\r\n<p>I certify that I have read (or have read to me) and fully understand the above post-operative instructions.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature}</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),
