aution around the eye area.</p>\r\n<p>No swimming for one week after your surgery.&nbsp; You may resume your exercise routine after your one-day exam; eye protection is recommended.</p>\r\n<p>Cigarette/Cigar smoke may irritate the eye following surgery and should be avoided for 5 days after.</p>\r\n<p>Your first follow-up exam is scheduled {TEXTBOX_LARGE} office.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient Signature</p>\r\n<p>{WITNESS SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Columbus Office: (614)781-0499 or 1-800-475-2113</p>\r\n<p>Mansfield Office: (614)781-0499</p>'),
(43,'Post Op AK/RK','<p>&nbsp;Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p>Date: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p>- Resting the day of surgery is advised.</p>\r\n<p>- TobraDex (antibiotic drop): One drop in the operative eye(s) four times daily for one week, then two times a day&nbsp; for the second week post-op,</p>\r\n<p>- DO NOT RUB YOUR EYE as this leads to improper healing of the incision.</p>\r\n<p>- Foreign body sensations, or &quot;scratchiness,&quot; light sinsitivity, glare, and are common during&nbsp; the immediate recovery period.</p>\r\n<p>- Pain is not expected.&nbsp; Should you experience pain, please call the office.&nbsp; If it is after hours, call ReVision and push &quot;0&quot; and leave a detailed message with the night operator.&nbsp; The doctor will be notifed and call you back.</p>\r\n<p>- You may experience dryness following your surgery.&nbsp; We recommend a preservative-free&nbsp; artificial tear to lubricate your eyes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>- You should expect your vision to fluctuate during the first 3-4 weeks post-op recovery period.</p>\r\n<p>- Avoid make-up, lotions, and after-shave for 2 days after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>- You may wash your face or shower but avoid rubbing across your eyes for one week after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>- No swimming for one week after your surgery.&nbsp; Avoid skydiving, scuba diving, and racquestball sports for one month after surgery, then eye protection is recommended.&nbsp; Boxing/karate are prohibited indefinitely.</p>\r\n<p>- You may resume other excercise routines the next day; eye protection is recommended.</p>\r\n<p>- Cigarette/cigar smoke will irritate the eye and can affect healing and should be avoided for one week after surgery.</p>\r\n<p>Your first follow-up appointment is scheduled at {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} in {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM}office.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patient Signature</p>\r\n<p>{WITNESS SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Columbus Office: (614)781-0499 or 1-800-475-2113</p>\r\n<p>Mansfield Office: (419)525-3737 or 1-888-775-3937</p>'),
(44,'Bandage Contact Lens','<p>Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITITAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DO NOT RUB YOUR EYE. Take your prescription pain medication with some food every 4-6 hrs. As needed for pain. Do not drive or drink alcohol when taking the drugs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your bandage contact lens needs to stay in place for 3 days and nights. You may experience varying degrees of discomfort or pain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your Bandage Contact Lens comes out do not attempt to replace it. Do the following:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. Expect increased pain. Take your prescription pain medication and rest with your eyes closed. An ice pack may help to relieve pain, 10min. on, 10min off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Call the office. After hours; call ReVision (phone numbers below); push &quot;0&quot;, leave a message with the night operator and a doctor will be notified.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TobraDex (antibiotic drop): One drop in the operative eye(s) four times daily for one week after surgery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may use&nbsp;&nbsp;Voltaren Ophthalmic drops is experiencing&nbsp;pain: Use&nbsp;one drop every 4 hours for 3 times&nbsp;on a day&nbsp;of surgery; one drops every 6-8 hours 2 times on the second and third day after surgery, then stop these drops.&nbsp;Do not use&nbsp;Voltaren unless&nbsp;you are experiencing pain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Expect light sensitivity, glare, halos, and dryness following your surgery.&nbsp; We recommend a preservative-free artificial tear to lubricate your eyes.&nbsp; These drops should be used throughout the day during the first month after surgery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Foreign body sensations, or &quot;scratchiness,&quot; light sensitivity, glare, halos, excessive tearing, burning are common. Your vision will be blured, hazy &amp; fluctuate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may experience dryness following your surgery. Use a preservation-free artificial tear to lubricate your eyes beginning the day after your surgery. These drops should be used throughout the day during the first month after surgery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your vision may fluctuate the first several weeks of your recovery period.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Avoid make-up, lotions, and after-shave for 3 days after surgery.&nbsp; You may wash your face or shower but avoid rubbing across your eyes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No swimming for one week after your surgery. You may resume your exercise routine after your one-day exam; eye protection is recommended.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cigarette/Cigar smoke may irritate the eye following surgery and should be avoided for 5 days after.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your first follow-up exam is scheduled at&nbsp;{TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} in {TEXTBOX_MEDIUM} office.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Patient Signature</p>\r\n\r\n<p>{Nurse&#39;s Signature}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Columbus Office: (614)781-0499 or 1-800-475-2113</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mansfield Office: (614)781-0499</p>\r\n'),
(45,'Corneal Transplant','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Corneal Transplant Post Operative Instructions</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. Some redness, light sensitivity and tearing are normal following corneal transplant surgery.&nbsp; You may experience a&nbsp; scratchy sensation after surgery.&nbsp; The discomfort following corneal transplant surgery usually requires no more than Tylenol or other non-aspirin products for relief.&nbsp; If this is insufficient, your should call the office.</p>\r\n<p>2. You may have some mattering following your corneal transplant surgery.&nbsp; Moisten a clean washcloth with warm tap water, wring and gently wipe with the washcloth to cleanse the eyelid.&nbsp; Repeat this procedure as often as necessary.&nbsp; A warm compress is soothing and beneficial to the eye.&nbsp; DO NOT RUB THE EYE.</p>\r\n<p>3. Light activity is permitted and encouraged.&nbsp; You may read or watch T.V.&nbsp; You may walk outside; ride in a car, train, plane or bus.&nbsp; Dr. Schumer will answer questions with regard to driving.&nbsp; You may shower or bathe, shampoo your hair, or visit your hair stylist.&nbsp; Avoid getting soap in your eye and wear your shield at the hair stylist.</p>\r\n<p>4. You may notice some increased sensitivity to light. Sunglasses may be helpful; wear them as needed.</p>\r\n<p>5. Avoid Straining, exerting and heavy lifting until advised otherwise by Dr. Schumer.&nbsp; Avoid bumping or rubbing the operative eye.&nbsp; You may bend or stoop to do things such as picking up the newspaper and tying your shoes.&nbsp; However, avoid bending for a long period of time.&nbsp; You may do light housework, light yard work or light exercise.&nbsp; (No jogging, bowling, or jarring sports.&nbsp; No swimming for 1-2 months).</p>\r\n<p>6. The eye shield should be worn at night or when napping to provide protection to the operative eye.&nbsp; You may sleep on either side or on your back. You need to wear some eye protection at all times, such as regular glasses, sunglases or the eye shield.</p>\r\n<p>7. Eye drops are necessary following surgery to promote healing, provide comfort, and prevent infection.&nbsp; Follow the instructions below to avoid placing pressure on the eye when these drops are instilled.</p>\r\n<p><strong>PREDNISOLONE ACETATE: 1 DROP IN OPERATIVE EYE 4 TIMES A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>VIGAMOX: 1 DROP IN OPERATIVE EYE 4 TIMES A DAY.</strong></p>\r\n<p>8. Instillation of drops:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wash hands thoroughly.&nbsp; Instill eye drops inside the lower lid while gazing upward with your eyes.&nbsp; It is not necessary to place the drop directly on the eye.&nbsp; Pull down the lower lid and apply the drop in the lower lid.</p>\r\n<p>9. Your next appointment will be scheduled or confirmed as you leave the office with each visit.</p>\r\n<p><strong>IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS OR FEEL THAT SOMETHING IS UNUSUAL, DO NOT HESITATE TO CALL DR. SCHUMER/ DR. WARING AT (419)525-3737 OR TOLL FREE (888)775-3937.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>{SIGNATURE}</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Patient\'s Signature:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Date: {DATE}</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>'),
(46,'Crystalens Post Op Instructions','<p>Congratulations for choosing <strong>Craystalens,</strong>&nbsp; the accommodation intraocular lens.&nbsp;&nbsp; You should enjoy this adjustable lens and the wonderful visual experience it can give you.&nbsp; A few things to the aware of:</p>\r\n<p>We would like you to obey a few rules during your post op period.</p>\r\n<p>-Please use your eye drops as you have been directed.</p>\r\n<p>-Please use your reading glasses (+1.25 or&nbsp;+1.75) for all intermediate and near tasks (finger tips to nose) for 10 days after implantation.</p>\r\n<p>-Reading glasses should be discontinued after the initial 10 day period.&nbsp; If you need to use any reading glasses after the initial 10 day period do not use anything more than a +1.25</p>\r\n<p>-After your 10 day post op period, exercise the muscles that move the lens in your eye by concentrating on objects at distance and near.&nbsp; Allow yourself time when changing back and forth.&nbsp; Reading every day for 15 minutes is also great exercise to strengthen this muscle.</p>\r\n<p>-Remember you have not used this muscle for many years and the only way to strengthen it, is by using it.&nbsp; Similar to having your knee replaced you would have to go through physicial therapy to strengthen your knee.&nbsp; The same thing is necessary to achieve the near vision you are looking for.&nbsp; You will continue to see improvement with your near vision over the next 3 to 6 months.</p>\r\n<p>-You should expect to have good distance and intermediate vision very quickly.&nbsp; This intermediate vision is a huge benefit, you would not have achieved this if you would have chosen another lens.</p>\r\n<p>-If you find your vision fluctuating it could be caused by poor tear quality.&nbsp; Please be sure to let us know, we can offer you some artificial tears to help you in this regard.</p>\r\n<p>Please call us at (614)781-0499 or 800-475-2113 if you have any additional questions or concerns.</p>\r\n<p>{SIGNATURE}</p>\r\n<p>Patient\'s Signature</p>\r\n<p>{Nurse\'s Signature}</p>');
