c was instilled in the eye.&nbsp;A groove incision was made with the Diamond blade at 0 .25mm at approximately 10 o&rsquo;clock position just anterior to the limbal vessels.&nbsp;The Diamond blade fully extended was inserted into the clear cornea up to the shoulder of the blade and then the angle of the blade is changed so that it is in the plane of the iris and then the anterior chamber is entered.&nbsp;A 27 gauge bent-tipped needle was used to make a continuous tear capsulorrhexis.&nbsp;A 27-gauge cannula attached to a syringe filled with balanced salt solution was then introduced to perform hydrodissection of the nucleus from the posterior layer of cortex.&nbsp;The phacoemulsification handpiece was inserted and phacoemulsification was performed.&nbsp;The nucleus was emulsified primarily in the posterior chamber.&nbsp;Cortical materials were removed using the irrigating and aspirating unit. Viscoelastic was instilled in the anterior chamber and in the posterior capsular bag.&nbsp;The capsule appeared entirely intact with an intact capsulorrhexis and an intact posterior capsular bag.&nbsp;The delivery tip for the lens was introduced into the corneal incision just into the anterior chamber and then intraocular lens implant was slowly injected into the posterior capsular bag.&nbsp;The residual Viscoelastic material was removed with the I&amp;A tip.&nbsp;Balanced salt solution was injected into the eye to fill it to the normal pressure.&nbsp;The eye was tested by pressing on the eye and the incision was noted to be watertight.&nbsp;The chamber remained deep.&nbsp;One drop of Pilocarpine 2% was applied to the eye.&nbsp;Antibiotic ointment was applied.&nbsp;The patient was taken to the recovery area in good condition. </span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>{LAST NAME}{MIDDLE INITIAL}{PATIENT FIRST NAME}{DOB}</p>\r\n<p>{SURGEON NAME}{DOS}</p>',311,0,0),
(108,'Crystalens Implant','<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman\">PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}, {SITE}</span></span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman\">POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS},{SITE}</span></span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman\">OPERATIVE PROCEDURE:<strong> </strong>{PROCEDURE}{SITE}</span></span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman\">\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in -0.25in 0pt 0in\"><b><span style=\"font-size: 12pt\">DESCRIPTION:</span></b><span style=\"font-size: 12pt\"> The patient was admitted to the surgery center. Eye drops were instilled as ordered on arrival. Betadine solution diluted 1:1 with normal balanced salt solution was instilled. The peri-bulbar block administered by anesthesia. Refer to anesthesia record for</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in -0.25in 0pt 0in\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt\">medications used and amounts administered. The Honan balloon was placed on the eye at a pressure level of 30mm of mercury prior to surgery. The eye was tested and found to have good anesthesia and akinesia. The patient was taken to the operating room and prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. The operating microscope was positioned and the lid speculum introduced. A stab paracentesis was placed at approximately 12 o&rsquo;clock position in clear cornea using the Diamond blade fully extended. Viscoelastic was instilled in the eye. A groove incision was made with the Diamond blade at 0 .25mm at approximately 10 o&rsquo;clock position just anterior to the limbal vessels. The Diamond blade fully extended was inserted into the clear cornea up to the shoulder of the blade and then the angle of the blade is changed so that it is in the plane of the iris and then the anterior chamber is entered. A 27 gauge bent-tipped needle was used to make a continuous tear capsulorrhexis. A 27-gauge cannula attached to a syringe filled with balanced salt solution was then introduced to perform hydrodissection of the nucleus from the posterior layer of cortex. The phacoemulsification handpiece was inserted and phacoemulsification was performed. The nucleus was emulsified primarily in the posterior chamber. Cortical materials were removed using the irrigating and aspirating unit. Viscoelastic was instilled in the anterior chamber and in the posterior capsular bag. The capsule appeared entirely intact with an intact capsulorrhexis and an intact posterior capsular bag. The delivery tip for the Crystalens lens was introduced into the corneal incision just into the anterior chamber and then intraocular lens implant was slowly injected into the posterior capsular bag. The residual Viscoelastic material was removed with the I&amp;A tip. Balanced salt solution was injected into the eye to fill it to the normal pressure. The eye was tested by pressing on the eye and the incision was noted to be watertight. The chamber remained deep. Antibiotic ointment was applied. The patient was taken to the recovery area in good condition. </span></div>\r\n</span></span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><b>{LAST NAME}{MIDDLE INITIAL}{PATIENT FIRST NAME}{DOB}</b></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">\r\n<p>{SURGEON NAME}{DOS}</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>',312,0,0),
(104,'YAG','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">{PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}{SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">{PROCEDURE}{SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">{POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}{SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Upon admission the patient the patient received one drop of Alcaine. The eye was dilated with one drop of Phenylephrine 2.5% and Tropicamide 1%. One drop of Iopidine 0.5% was instilled in the operative eye. Immediately prior to the procedure an addition drop of Alcaine was instilled in both eyes to eliminate the blink reflex. The patient was positioned carefully at the Zeiss YAG Laser with the head fixed in the correct position, the chin being in the chin rest and the forehead against the forehead band. A YAG contact lens was applied to the operative eye. The YAG laser machine was set as indicated. The patient was directed to look leftward to eliminate corneal reflex. Several bursts of YAG laser energy were applied to the membrane, and the patient was then directed to look to the right to extend the opening toward that side and easily bypass the edge of the iris.&nbsp;The patient was directed to look slightly above and slightly below similarly to enlarge the opening in the posterior chamber. The number of YAG laser bursts used are as indicated. The posterior capsule opening being made just slightly larger than the pupillary opening.&nbsp;Care was taken to ensure that the laser was always focused on the posterior chamber capsule to avoid damage to the ocular tissue or lens implant. The procedure was completed without complication or discomfort.&nbsp;The patient was discharged to home under self-care. The patient was given post-procedure instructions and instructed to return to the clinic in approximately one week for follow-up evaluation.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 0pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p>{LAST NAME}{PATIENT FIRST NAME}{MIDDLE INITIAL}</p>\r\n<p>{SURGEON NAME}{DOS}</p>',307,0,0),
(130,'Intacs Op Note','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was taken into the surgery room and placed in the supine position.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual manner. A lid wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; The center portion of the patient\'s cornea was marked.&nbsp; The bull\'s eye sight was then inken and centered on the center portion of the cornea with the incision site at degrees.&nbsp; Pachymetry measurement of was taken at this site, and a diamond knife was set a depth of mm.&nbsp; An incision was made over this pre-placed mark 1.8mm in length.&nbsp; The synechia hook was used to dissect the base of the incision.&nbsp; The suction ring was then placed onto the eye, centered with the bulls eye site.&nbsp; Low suction was obtained and then higher suction.&nbsp; A cloackwise pigtail probe was placed into the suction ring and then rotated so that the probe went into the coreneal channel in a clockwise fashion.&nbsp; This was removed and then the couter-clockwise pigtail probe was used to dissect the cornea on the counter-clockwise direction.&nbsp; The suction was released and segment(s) were placed into the channels.&nbsp; The synechia hook was used to position the segment(s) appropriately.&nbsp; A nylon suture was placed through the incision.&nbsp; The knot(s) was trimmed and buried.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed, and the patient was discharged in stable condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Discharge Summary:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was given discharge post-operative instructions and a follow-up appointment.&nbsp; The patient was then released from ReVision in good ambulatory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Additional Notes/ Complications: None</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>',350,0,0),
(131,'DSEK Op Note','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;The patient was taken to the operating room and placed in the supine postion.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; Attention was the directed to the donor tissue which was examined under the microscope prior to surgery and found to be of excellent quality.&nbsp; This tissue was placed into the Hessberg Baron punch.&nbsp; A 9mm blade was used to punch the central corneal button.&nbsp; This was set aside in BSS for later use.&nbsp; Attention was then placed back to the patient\'s eye.&nbsp; An 8mm mark was then placed onto the anterior corneal surface.&nbsp; A stab incision was made at the limbus with a sharp super blade.&nbsp; Staarvisc was injected through this incision in order to deepen the anterior chamber.&nbsp; At this time 5mm calipers were marked on the clear corneal temporal area.&nbsp; A keratome knife was then used to make an incision over this caliper mark extending 5mm.&nbsp; A reverse Sinsky Hook was placed through the clear corneal incision.&nbsp; Descemet\'s membrane was scored 360 degrees on the 8mm mark.&nbsp; An angled spatula was then placed into the anterior chamber and Descemet\'s membrance was stripped from the posterior aspect of the patien\'s cornea and was removed from the eye. Irrigation aspiration was then used to remove the Staarvisc from the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A reverse sinsky was used to score the outer edge of the stomal surface.&nbsp; A bent 25 gauge needle was used to roughen the peripheral edges of the patient\'s endothelium.&nbsp; With the use of .12 forceps and McPherson forceps, the posterior lammellar portion of the donor tissue was folded into a 60/40 configuration after the Staarvisc was placed onto the endothelial surface.&nbsp; The donor tissue was then grasped with the insertion forceps.&nbsp; The donor tissue was inserted through the clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; Once in the anterior chamber, it was released.&nbsp; Three interrupted 10-0 Nylon sutures were placed through the clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; Air on 3cc syringe with a 30g needle was placed into the anterior chamber unfolding the donor tissue.&nbsp; The cornea roller was then used to position the tissue centrally onto the patient\'s cornea.&nbsp; A large amount of air was placed into the chamber and allowed to remain in place for 13-16 minutes.&nbsp; The majority of the air was removed from the anterior chamber and replaced with BSS.&nbsp; The eye was left with intraocular pressure measuring around 10.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patien was discharged in stable condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Discharge Summary:&nbsp; The patient was given post-operative instructions and a follow-up appointment.&nbsp; The patient was then released from ReVsion in good ambulatory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>',350,0,0),
(132,'Phaco with DSEK','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was taken to the operating room and placed in the supine position.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; A wire lid speculum was placed into the left eye.&nbsp; A stab incision was made at the limbus with a sharp super balde.&nbsp; Staarvisc was injected through this incision in order to deepen the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A 2.8mm keratome knife was used to make a clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; A bent needle cystitome was then placed through the clear corneal temporal incision to perform a 360 degree continuous tear capsulorhexis.&nbsp; Lidocaine 1% PF on a blunt needle was used to perform hydrodissection and hydrodelineation.&nbsp; Phacoemulsification was used to remove the nucleaus from the capsular bag.&nbsp; Irrigation aspiration was used to remove the cortical material from the capsular bag.&nbsp; Staarvisc was injected into the capsular bag in order to expand it.&nbsp; A 20.0 diopter lens was opened, inspected and loaded into the injector.&nbsp; The injector was placed through the clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; The IOL was injected into the capsular bag.&nbsp; Irrigation aspiration was used to remove the Staarvisc from the capsular bag.&nbsp; An 8mm mark was then placed onto the corneal surface.&nbsp; A reverse Sinsky Hook was used to score the endothelium of the patient\'s cornea 360 degrees at the 8mm mark.&nbsp; An angled spatula was used to strip Decemet\'s membrane from the posterior aspect of the patient\'s cornea and was removed from the eye.&nbsp; A bent 25 gauge needle was used to score the outer edge of stormal surface.&nbsp; Attention was then directed to the donor tissue which was examined under the microscope prior to surgery and found t be of excellent quality.&nbsp; This tissue was placed into the Hessberg Baron punch.&nbsp; A 9mm trephine was used to punch the central portion of the donor tissue.&nbsp; The donor tissue was then inserted into the patient\'s cornea, and the clear temporal incision was extended to 5mm with a keratome knife.&nbsp; BSS was injected into the anterior chamber after all the Amvisc was removed from the anterior chamber.&nbsp; The donor tissue was then folded in a 60/40 configuration after Amvisc was placed onto theendothelialsurface.&nbsp; The insertion forceps were used to grasp the donor tissue.&nbsp; The donor tissue was placed through the clear corneal incision and then released into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; Three interrupted 10-0 Nylon sutures were placed through the clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; Once the incision was closed, air was introduced into the anterior chamber allowing the donor tissue to expand.&nbsp; A cornea roller was used on the corneal surface to position the transplanted tissue centrally onto the patient\'s cornea.&nbsp; A large air bubble was placed into the anterior chamber and left in place for 13-16 minutes.&nbsp; The majority of the air was removed and replaced with BSS.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The eye was left with the intraocular pressure measuring arond 10.&nbsp; An eye shield was placed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged in stable condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Discharge Summary:&nbsp; The patient was given post-operative instructions and a follow up appointment.&nbsp; The patient was the released from ReVision in good ambulatory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>',350,0,0),
(112,'Surgeon 2 OP Report','<p>PATIENT: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p>DATE OF SURGERY: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p>PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p>POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p>PROCEDURE: {PROCEDURE} {SITE}</p>\r\n<p>SURGEON: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p>Procedure/Findings: The patient was brought to the Operating Room where oxygen therapy was administered via oxygen swan. The patient received Lidocaine 2% gel topical anesthesia. The eye was prepped and draped in the routine sterile fashion. A lid speculum was inserted into the operative eye.</p>\r\n<p>A paracentesis site was performed at the limbus using a 1.2 mm V-lance knife. Viscoelastic was used to reform the anterior chamber followed by 0.3 cc of 1% Xylocaine MPF. Good intraoperative anesthesia was obtained. Clear cornea tunnel was dissected at the temporal limbus extending 2 mm into the clear cornea using a keratome blade. An anterior curvilinear continuous capsulorhexis was performed with the bent 25-guage needle and Utrata forceps.</p>\r\n<p>Following hydrodissection, the nucleus was removed with Phacoemulsification without complications. Cortical clean up was performed with automated irrigation and aspiration. Viscoelastic was used to reform the capsular bag.</p>\r\n<p>Intraocular lens was prepared to be placed. The intraocular lens was placed into the appropriate inserter, rinsed with balanced salt solution, placed through the surgical wound, and released into the capsular bag without complications. The lens was rotated until centered.</p>\r\n<p>The Viscoelastic was removed with the automated irrigation and aspiration. The wound was closed with stromal hydration. At the end of the case, the chamber was deep, the pupil round and the wound was watertight. Dexamethasone 2 mg subconjuctival injection was given in inferior fornix. Antibiotics and steriodal drops were instilled. The lid speculum was removed. A light pressure patch and eyeshield was applied.</p>\r\n<p>The patient tolerated the procedure and anesthesia well and the left the Operating Room in good condition.</p>',338,0,0),
