(114,'AK OP Note','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary:&nbsp;{TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was taken to the surgery room and place in the supine position.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; The appropriate degree arcuate mark was placed at the desired degree axis.&nbsp; A&nbsp; diamond knife set at the calculated depth was used to make incisions over the pre-placed corneal mark.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patien was discharged in stable condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>',350,0,0),
(115,'ECP ','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was taken into the OR prepped and draped in usual sterile manner.&nbsp; Lid speculum was inserted into the eye.&nbsp; A 2.8mm incision was made in the clear cornea temporally.&nbsp; An injection of Lidocaine 1% preservative free 0.5%ml was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected into the ciliary sulcus.&nbsp; The endoscopic probe was placed through the clear corneal incision and the ciliary body was easily visualized.&nbsp; Laser application was placed on each process of the ciliary body until the ciliary body turned white and slightly shrank.&nbsp; This was performed approximately&nbsp;300&nbsp;degrees of the ciliary body was treated without difficulty and without complication.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The endoscopic probe was removed.&nbsp; BSS was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; The wounds were found to be water tight.&nbsp; The&nbsp;Viscoelastic was removed with irrigation aspiration.&nbsp; The wounds were found to be water tight.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged in stable condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
(123,'Visian ICL','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; Two stab incisions were made at the limbus at the 8 o\'clock position and the 2 o\'clock position.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A 2.8 keratome knife was used to make a clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; This incision was extended to 3.2mm.&nbsp; The ICL was then removed from its sterile container,&nbsp;inspected under the microscope and found to be in good condition&nbsp;with no defects&nbsp;and loaded into the injector.&nbsp; Forceps were&nbsp;used to&nbsp;pull through the injector into its proper position.&nbsp; The injector tips was loaded into the injector handle.&nbsp; The ICL was engaged and then placed through the clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; The ICL was injected into the anterior chamber. With the ICL manipulator through the clear corneal stab incision, the footplates were placed just posterior to the iris.&nbsp; This was done in all four quadrants.&nbsp; The ICL was in good stable position.&nbsp; Irrigation aspiration was performed to remove the&nbsp;Viscoelastic from the anterior chamber.&nbsp; BSS was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; the wonds were found to be watertight.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed and the patient was discharged&nbsp;from Revision Advanced Surgery Center in good ambultory&nbsp;condition.</p>',350,0,0),
(116,'Phaco & ECP ','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was taken to the surgeon room and placed in the supine postion.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; A stab incision was made at the limbus with a super blade.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected through this incision in order to deepen the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A 2.8mm Keratome Knife was used to make a clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; A bent needle cystotome was placed through this temporal incision in order to perform a 360 degree continuous tear capsulorrhexis.&nbsp; Preservative free anelgesic&nbsp;on a blunt gauge needle was then used to perform hydrodissection and hydrodelineation.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was then injected using a blunt cannula.&nbsp; Phacoemulsification was used to remove the nucleus from the capsular bag and irrigation-aspiration was used to remove the cortical material ffrom the capsular bag.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected into the capsular bag in order to expand it.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The IOL was opened, inspected and found to be of excellent quality.&nbsp; It was loaded into the injector.&nbsp; This injector was placed through the clear corneal temporal incision and the IOL was injected into the capsular bag.&nbsp; the trailing haptic was placed into the capsular bag with McPherson forceps.&nbsp; The IOL was stable and in good, round, central position.&nbsp; Then irrigation-aspiration was used to remove the&nbsp;Viscoelastic from the capsular bag and anterior chamber.&nbsp; Balanced salt solution was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">At the conclusion of the phacoemulsification with posterior chamber IOL, Preservative free 1%&nbsp; lidocaine diluted with BSS was injected into the sulcus.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected into the ciliary sulcus.&nbsp; The endoscopic probe was placed through the clear corneal incision and the ciliary body was easily visualized.&nbsp; Laser application was placed on each process of the ciliary body until the ciliary body turned white and slightly shrank.&nbsp; This was performed approximately 300 degrees of the ciliary body was treated without difficulty and without complication.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The endoscopic probe was removed.&nbsp; The&nbsp;Viscoelastic was removed with irrigation and aspiration.&nbsp; BSS was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp;&nbsp; The wounds were found to be water tight.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged from Revision Advanced Surgery Center in&nbsp;good ambulatory&nbsp;condition.</p>',350,0,0),
(117,'Phaco ','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was taken to the surgery room and placed in the supine position.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; A stab incision was made at the limbus with a super blade.&nbsp; Amvisc was injected through this incision in order to deepen the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A 2.80mm Keratome knife was used to make a clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; A bent needle cystotome was placed through this temporal incision in order to perform a 360degree continuous tear capsulorrhexis. Local angelgesic on&nbsp;a blunt gauge needle was then used to perform hydrodyssection and hydrodelineation.&nbsp; Viscoelastic was then injected using a blunt cannula.&nbsp; Phacoemulsification was used to remove the nucleus from the capsular bag and irrigation-aspiration was used to remove the cortical material from the capsular bag.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected into the capsular bag in order to expand it. The IOL was opened, inspected and found to be of excellent quality.&nbsp; It was loaded into the injector.&nbsp; This injector was placed through the clear corneal temporal incision and the IOL was injected into the capsular bag.&nbsp; The trailing haptic was placed into the capsular bag with McPherson forceps.&nbsp; The IOL was stable and in a good, round, central position.&nbsp; The irrigation-aspiration was used to remove the Amvisc from the capsular bag and anterior chamber.&nbsp; Balanced salt solution was injected into the anterior chamber and the wounds were found to be watertight.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged from Revision Advanced Surgery Center in&nbsp;good ambulatory&nbsp;condition.</p>',350,0,0),
(119,'Phaco and AK w/ IOK ','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\r\n	ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	The patient was taken to the surgery room and placed in the supine position.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp;&nbsp;An AK procedure according to the predetermined plan.&nbsp; A stab incision was made at the limbus with a super blade.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic&nbsp;was injected through this incision in order to deepen the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A 2.8 mm Keratome knife was used to make a clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; A bent needle cystotome was placed through this temporal incision in order to perform a 360 degree continuous tear capsulorrhexis. 1% lido, PF, on a blunt gauge needle was then used to perform hydrodissection and hydrodelineation.&nbsp; Viscoelasticwas then injected using a blunt cannula.&nbsp;&nbsp;Phacomulsification was used to remove the nucleus from the capsular bag and irrigation-aspiration was used to remove the cortical material from the capsular bag.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected into the capsular bag in order to expand it.&nbsp; An IOL was opened, inspected and found to be of excellent quality.&nbsp; It was loaded into the injector.&nbsp; This injector was placed through the clear corneal temporal incision and the IOL was injected into the capsular bag.&nbsp; The trailing haptic was placed into the capsular bag with McPherson forceps.&nbsp; The IOL was stable and in a good, round, central position.&nbsp; Then irrigation-aspiration was used to remove the&nbsp;Viscoelastic from the capsular bag and anterior chamber.&nbsp; Balanced salt solution was injected into the anterior chamber and the wounds were found to be watertight.&nbsp; At this time, 0.1cc of Kenalog and Moxifloxacin mixture was injected into the posterior capsule using a blunt cannula.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patient was given post operative instructions and a follow-up appointment.&nbsp; The patient was then released from Revision Advanced Surgery Center in good ambulatory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME},M.D.</p>\r\n',350,0,0),
(124,'Verisyse IOL','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate topical&nbsp;anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; Calipers were used to mark medial and temporal, just inferior to the pupillary space.&nbsp; The 10mm cord length was marked for the enclavation sites then 5mm superiorly where the incision was going to be, centered on axis 85 degrees.&nbsp; Wescott scissors and .12 forceps were used to perform a superior periotomy.&nbsp; Cautery was used for hemostasis.&nbsp; A 2.8 keratome knife was used to make an incision into the sclera and split thickness dissection was made into the clear cornea.&nbsp; The anterior chamber was entered.&nbsp; Viscoelastic was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A sharp super blade was used to make the enclavation incisions, both at 10 and 2 o\'clock.&nbsp; The superior scleral incision was extended to a 5mm cord length.&nbsp; A Verisyse lens was opened and inspected and found to be in good condition with no defects and with the use of McPherson forceps was placed through the superior incision.&nbsp; It was rotated into position, just inferiorly to the pupillary margin.&nbsp; Enclavation was performed both medial and temporal haptics as the mid-peripheral iris was pulled through the haptics.&nbsp; The lens was stable and well centered.&nbsp; The viscoelastic was removed from the anterior chamber with a syringe and BSS.&nbsp; The superior incision was sutured with 3 interrupted 10-0 nylon sutures.&nbsp; The conjunctiva was brought up to the limbus and tacked into place with one 10-0 nylon suture.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The eye was protected with goggles and the patient was discharged Revision Advanced Surgery Center in good ambultory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
(120,'Phaco w/AK ','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepper and draped in the usual sterile manner. A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; An AK procedure was performed according to the predetermined plan.&nbsp; A stab incision was made at the limbus with super blade.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected through this incision in order to deepen the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A 2.8 mm Keratome knife was used to make a clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; A bent needle cystotome was placed through this temporal incision in order to perform a 360 degree continuous tear capsulorrhexis.&nbsp; 1% lido, PF, on a blunt gauge needle was then used to perform hydrodissection and hydrodelineation.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was then injected using a blunt cannula.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Phacoemulsification was used to remove the nulceus from the capsular bag and irrigation-aspiration was used to remove the cortical material from the capsular bag.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected into the capsular bag in order to expand it. An IOL was opened, inspected and found to be of excellent quality.&nbsp; It was loaded into the injector.&nbsp; This injector was placed through the clear corneal temporal incision and the IOL was injected into the capsular bag.&nbsp; The trailing haptic was placed into the capsular bag with McPherson forceps.&nbsp; The IOL was stable and in a good, round, central position.&nbsp; Then irrigation-aspiration was used to remove the&nbsp;Viscoelastic from the capsular bag and anterior chamber.&nbsp; Balanced salf solution was injected into the anterior chamber and the wounds were found to be watertight.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged from Revision Advanced Surgery Center in good ambulatory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
(121,'Reposition of IOL','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; A sinsky hook was used to open the previous wound.&nbsp; The anterior chamber was entered.&nbsp; The haptic of the displaced IOL was used to rotate the IOL into the correct position.&nbsp; BSS was used to refill the anterior chamber.&nbsp; The wound was found to be watertight.&nbsp; The patient tolerated the procedure well.&nbsp; Patient was discharged from Revision Advanced Surgery Center in good ambulatory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
(122,'Secondary IOL','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; A peritomy was performed temporarily.&nbsp; Cautery was used for hemostasis.&nbsp; With the use of a diamond knife a scleral incision was made and a tunnel then was formed into the clear cornea.&nbsp; The anterior chamber was entered.&nbsp;&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected into the anterior chamber in order to deepen it.&nbsp; An IOL was opened, inspected and found to be of excellent quality.&nbsp; It was inserted with McPherson forceps and then slid through the scleral tunnel incision into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; The IOL was rotated and stable and in good solid position.&nbsp; The wound was closed with interrupted 10.0 nylon sutures.&nbsp; Irrigation aspiration was performed to remove the&nbsp;Viscoelastic from the anterior chamber.&nbsp; The peritomy was put back into place and sutured with 1 interrupted 10.0 nylon suture.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed, a drop of Tobramycin was placed and the patient was discharged from Revision Advanced Surgery Center in good ambulatory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
(125,'Sup Keratectomy ','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye. A #64 Beaver blade was used to remove the superficial epithelium. &nbsp; A bandage contact lens was placed.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged&nbsp;from Revision Advanced Surgery Center in good ambulatory condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
(126,'Surface TX w/Mito C','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepper and draped in the usual sterile manner. A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; An trephine was used to score the epihelim.&nbsp; A well was placed onto the central portion of the cornea.&nbsp; 18% alcohol solution was placed into the well.&nbsp; This was allowed to contact the cornea for 45 seconds.&nbsp; The alcohol solution was then removed with a weck cell sponge, and BSS was used to irrigate the eye.&nbsp; A weck cell sponge was used to dry the cornea.&nbsp; The epithelium was the peeled with a blunt spatula.&nbsp; A weck cell sponge was used to dry the excess moisture on the surface of the Bowman\'s layer.&nbsp; The laser was then centered with proper orientation.&nbsp; Fixation was directed for the patient at the blinking light, and the laser ablation was applied.&nbsp; The laser ablation was delivered over the pupil opening, maintaining centration througout the procedure.&nbsp; A 6.0mm sponge soaked with 1 drop of Mitomycin-C 0.02% solution was placed onto the ablated area of the cornea for 30 seconds.&nbsp; BSS was used to irrigate the eye.&nbsp; A weck cell sponge was used to absorb excess fluid.&nbsp; A bandage contact lens was placed and a drop of Tobradex was instilled in the operated eye.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged to the post-op area for observation.&nbsp; Postoperative instructions were explained and a follow-up appointment was given to the patient before discharge.&nbsp; The patient was examined under the slip lamp to assure the proper BCL position.&nbsp; The eye was again shielded.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
(127,'Visian ICL (Bilateral)','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">OD:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate&nbsp;topical&nbsp;anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A wire lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; Two stab incisions were made at the limbus at the 8 o\'clock position and the 2 o\'clock position.&nbsp; Ocucoat was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A 2.8mm keratome knife was used to make a clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; This incision was extended to 3.2mm.&nbsp; The ICL was then removed from its sterile container, inspected under the microscope and loaded into the injector.&nbsp; Using forceps, the lens was pulled through the injector into its proper position.&nbsp; The injector tip was loaded into the injector handle.&nbsp; The ICL was engaged and then placed through the clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; The ICL was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; With the ICL manipulator through the clear corneal stab incision, the footplates were placed just posterior to the iris.&nbsp; This was done in all four quadrants.&nbsp; The ICL was in good stable position.&nbsp; Irrigation aspiration was performed to remove the Ocucoat from the anterior chamber.&nbsp; BSS was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; The wounds were found to be water tight.&nbsp; The lid speculum was remvoved.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">OS:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The second eye was then prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined,&nbsp;a lid speculum was placed into the eye. Two stab incisions were made at the limbus at the 8 o\'clock position and the 2 o\'clock position. Ocucoat was injected into the anterior chamber. A 2.8mm keratome knife was used to make a clear corneal temporal incision. This incision was extended to 3.2mm. The ICL was then removed from its sterile container, inspected under the microscope and loaded into the injector. Using forceps, the lens was pulled through the injector into its proper position. The injector tip was loaded into the injector handle. The ICL was engaged and then placed through the clear corneal temporal incision. The ICL was injected into the anterior chamber. With the ICL manipulator through the clear corneal stab incision, the footplates were placed just posterior to the iris. This was done in all four quadrants. The ICL was in good stable position. Irrigation aspiration was performed to remove the Ocucoat from the anterior chamber. BSS was injected into the anterior chamber. The wounds were found to be water tight. The lid speculum was remvoved.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
