(129,'Cataract','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was take to the surgery room and placed in the supine position. After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; Attention was then directed to the donor tissue which was examined under the microscope prior to surgery and found to be of excellent quality.&nbsp; This tissue was placced into the Hessberg Baron punch.&nbsp; A 9mm blade was used to punch the central corneal button.&nbsp; This was set aside in BSS for later use.&nbsp; Attention was then placed back to the patient\'s eye.&nbsp; An 8mm mark was then placed onto the anterior corneal surface.&nbsp; A stab incision was made at the limbus with a sharp super blade.&nbsp; Staarvisc was injected through this incision in order to deepen the anterior chamber.&nbsp; At this time 5mm calipers were marked on the clear corneal temporal area.&nbsp; A keratome knife was then used to make an incision over this caliper mark extending 5mm.&nbsp; A reverse Sinsky Hook was placed though the clear corneal incision.&nbsp; Descemet\'s membrane was scored 360 degrees on the 8mm mark.&nbsp; An angled spatula was then placed into the anterior chamber and Descemet\'s membrane was stripped from the the posterior aspect of the patient\'s cornea and was removed from the eye.&nbsp; Irrigation aspiration was then used to remove the Staarvisc from the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A reverse sinsky was used to score the outer edge of the stromal surface.&nbsp; A bent 25 gauge needle was used to roughen the peripheral edges of the patient\'s endothelium.&nbsp; With the use of .12 forceps and McPherson forceps, the posterior lamellar portion of the donor tissue was folded in a 60/40 configuration after Staarvisc was placed onto the endothelial surface.&nbsp; The donor tissue was then grasped with the insertion forceps.&nbsp; The donor tissue was inserted through the clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; Once in the air chamber, it was released.&nbsp; Three interrupted 10-0 Nylon sutures were placed through the clear corneal temporal incision.&nbsp; Air on a 3cc syringe with a 30g needle was placed into the anterior chamber unfolding the donor tissue.&nbsp; The cornea roller was then used to position the tissue centrally onto the patient\'s cornea.&nbsp; A large amount of air was placed into the chamber and allowed to remain in place to 13-16 minutes.&nbsp; The majority of the air was removed from the anterior chamber and replaced with BSS.&nbsp; The eye was left with intraocular pressue measuring around 10.&nbsp; The lid speculum was removed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged in stable condition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>',350,0,0),
(134,'Chalazion','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was taken to the operating room and placed in the supine position.&nbsp; After adequate anesthesia was determined, the patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; A chalazion clamp was placed on the lid.&nbsp; It was everted and using a 11 blade a vertical incision was made into the tarsal plate.&nbsp; A currette was used to remove a large amount of material from the inside of the chalazion.&nbsp; The fiber capsule was excised with .12 forceps and wescott scissors.&nbsp; The chalazion clamp was removed.&nbsp; Tobradex ointment was placed into the right eye.&nbsp; The eye was pressure patched.&nbsp; The patient was discharged in stable condition.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Discharge Summary:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was given post-operative instructions and a follow up appointment.&nbsp; The patient was the released from ReVision in good ambulatory condition.</p>',350,0,0),
(135,'LASIK','<p style=\"text-align: center\">ReVision Advanced Surgery Center</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Date of Surgery: {DOS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Pre-Op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Post-Op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Procedure(s):</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Primary: {PRIMARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Secondary: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Tertiary: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Microkeratome:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">[&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 20071 Nidek</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">[&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 20185 Nidek</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Blade:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">[&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ]&nbsp; 130</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">[&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ] 160&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Flap Diameter:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">[&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;8.5mm</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">[&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ]&nbsp;&nbsp; 9.5mm</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" width=\"200\">\r\n    <tbody>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; OD</td>\r\n            <td style=\"text-align: center\" height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp; #</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>PreOp&nbsp;Central Pach</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>IntraOp Central Pach</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>Flap Thickness</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>Ablation Depth</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>Residual Bed Depth</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>N/A Hyperopic Tx</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n    </tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" width=\"200\">\r\n    <tbody>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td style=\"text-align: center\">OS</td>\r\n            <td style=\"text-align: center\" height=\"30\" width=\"30\">#</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>PreOp Central Pach</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>IntraOp Central Pach</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>Flap Thickness</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>Ablation Depth</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>Residual Bed Depth</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>N/A Hyperopic Tx</td>\r\n            <td height=\"30\" width=\"30\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n    </tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">Operative Note:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was taken to the laser surgery suite and assisted to the supine position.&nbsp; The eye was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.&nbsp; After adequate topical anesthesia was determinedm, a lid speculum was placed into the eye.&nbsp; The microkeratome was carefully examined for proper installation of the blade and micron plate, and it was run across the suction ring to assure a smooth movement.&nbsp; The suction ring was placed onto the surface of they eye and centered on the previous mark.&nbsp; The suction was engaged and adequte pressure was obtained on the suction gauge.&nbsp; Proper intraocular pressure was obtained.&nbsp; Once the microkeratome was engaged, the foot-switch was pressed and the mircokeratome moved across the eye in its full excursion.&nbsp; The microkeratome was reversed with the foot-switch and suction was released.&nbsp; The flap was reflected with a spatula.&nbsp; The laser was then centered with proper orientation.&nbsp; Fixation was directed for the patient, and the laser ablation was applied.&nbsp; The laser ablation was delivered over the pupil opening, maintaining centration throughout the procedure.&nbsp; Once the laser ablation was completed, the stromal bed was irrigated and the flap was placed back into position.&nbsp; This assured that there was not wrinkling in the cap.&nbsp; Oxygen at 2.5 liters was applied to the cap for drying and a striae test was performed to assure proper cap adherence.&nbsp; Tobradex and methylcellulose was appied to the surface of the cornea and the lid speculum and drapes were removed.&nbsp; The patient was discharged to the post-op area for observation.&nbsp; Postoperative instructions were explained and a follow-up appointment in one day was given to the patient before discharge.&nbsp; The patient was examined under the slit lamp to assure the proper position and placement of the cap without any evidence of wrinkling.&nbsp; The eye was again shielded.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">DISCHARGE SUMMARY:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">The patient was given post operative instructions and a follow-up appointment.&nbsp; The patient was then released from ReVison in good ambulatory condition.</p>',350,0,0),
(149,'Cataract','<p>PATIENT: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DATE: {DATE}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PRE-OPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Visually significant cataract {SITE}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>POST-OPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Same</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SURGEON: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PROCEDURE: {PROCEDURE}, {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}{SITE}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OPERATION: The patient was brought into the OR after IV sedation and peri-bulbar block by the anesthesiologist. After attachment of appropriate monitoring equipment, the patient was prepped and draped in a sterile manner. A lid speculum was inserted. A fornix based conjunctival flap was fashioned with .12mm forceps and Wescott scissors. Hemostasis was achieved with bipolar cautery. A scleral incision was created with a keratome. The anterior chamber was reformed with viscoelastic agent. A paracentesis was created. A continuous curvilinear capsulorhexis was fashioned with a cystotome and capsulorhexis forceps. BSS was irrigated under the capsular rim and a posterior fluid wave was noted. The nucleus was rotated with the irrigating tip. Hydrodelineation was effected using the irrigating tip. Phacoemulsification was then performed in a &#39;stop and chop&#39; manner. Phacoemulsification time: ______. Aspiration of cortical material was effected with the Simcoe I/A unit. At the conclusion of this, the posterior capsule was noted to be intact. The capsular bag was reinflated with viscoelastic agent. A posterior chamber intra-ocular lens was inserted into the capsular bag. The viscoelastic agent was removed with the Simcoe unit. The anterior chamber was reformed with BSS. The incision was dried, tested for leakage and found to exhibit none. The conjunctival flap was reapproximated with jeweler tip cautery. Antibiotic ointment was applied to the eye. The operative drapes and speculum were removed and the eye was closed and covered with a sterile dressing and eye shield. The patient left the operating room in a stable condition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Post-Operative Plan - See patient postoperatively 24 hours after surgery. Patient to receive postoperative instructions for care and precautions of the eye from the surgery center which were adopted by the medical staff of Surgisite Boston. A copy of these instructions is maintained in the policy and procedure manual of Surgisite Boston.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>{SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n',377,0,0),
(137,'Facet Joint Injection Lumbar','<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Patient Name: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {LAST NAME}</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Primary&nbsp;Procedure: {PROCEDURE}</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Secondary Procedure: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Tertiary Procedure: {TERTIARY PROCEDURE}</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Surgeon Name: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">History and physical examination were reviewed. Risks benefits, and alternatives to the procedure were discussed with the patient. All questions were answered up to the patient\'s satisfaction and voluntary informed consent was obtained. Intravenous line was secure. The patient was taken to the operating room and was placed in prone position on the fluoroscopy table. Regular operating room monitors were placed by the anesthesiologist.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">The patient was then placed in the _________________ lateral decubitus position on the table and the neck was then prepped and draped in usual sterile fashion.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Next, subcutaneous 1% lidocaine was instilled to the superficial soft tissue over the target area for local anesthesia. Under fluoroscopy guidance, the _________ lateral approach was used to identify the spinous process and articular pillars of _____________, _________________, and ______________ in lateral view on the camera. __________ G needle was then placed through the skin and soft tissue and advanced to make contact with bone at the mid point on the articular pillar of the respective levels. After repeated negative aspiration for blood, CSF, or any other body fluid _______ cc of ______% bupivacaine was injected easily and carefully. This solution was mixed with 20 mg of Kenalog for each location and the similar procedure was performed for all other levels. No paresthesia orsigns of intravascular injection of local anesthesia was noted. The patient tolerated the procedure very well and was transferred to the recovery room in stable condition. The patient was discharged with appropriate instruction.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\">&nbsp;</div>',378,0,0),
(138,'Cervical Interlaminar Epidural Steroid Injection','<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><b><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Indications: Cervical radiculopathy</span></b></div>\r\n<div style=\"line-height: normal; margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><b><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Procedure:</span></b><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"> History and physical examination were reviewed. Risks benefits, and alternatives to the procedure were discussed with the patient. All questions were answered up to the patient\'s satisfaction and voluntary informed consent was obtained. Intravenous line was secure. The patient was taken to the operating room and was placed in prone position on the fluoroscopy table. Regular operating room monitors were placed by the anesthesiologist.</span></div>\r\n<p><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 10pt\">A pillow was placed under the patient\'s chest to increase the cervical interlaminar space. C7-T1 interspace was visualized under fluoroscopy guidance and the skin over the target area was anesthetized with 1% lidocaine #25-guage needle and 3 cc of lidocaine. A #20 gauge Touhey epidural needle was inserted and was advanced under direct fluoroscopy guidance and intermittent checking towards the C7-T1 interspace. The epidural space was identified by loss of resistance technique and there was no fluid, blood, or CSF noted. The needle tip placement was reconfirmed with 0.5 cc of 180 Omnipaque and the epidurogram was noted. The patient did not complain of any paresthesia. At this point, after negative aspiration 40 mg kenalog and 4 cc of 0.25% preservative-free bupivacaine was injected slowly and steadily. The needle was then removed and a sterile Betadine was applied. There were no signs of paresthesia or any intravascular injection of tine anesthetic noted. The patient tolerated the procedure very well and was transferred to the recovery room in stable condition. The patient was discharged with appropriate instruction.</span></p>',378,0,0),
(139,'Lumbar Dorsal Median Branch Block','<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 10pt\">Indications: Lower back pain and facet pain.</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 10pt\">Procedure: <span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\">History and physical of the patient was reviewed. Risk</span><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\">s</span><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\">, benefits, and alternatives to the procedure were discussed with the patient, and all questions were answered to the patient\'s satisfaction. An informed consent was obtained. Intravenous line was secured. The patient was taken to the operating room and placed prone o</span><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\">n</span><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\"> the fluoroscopy table. Regular operating room monitors were placed</span><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\">, and the patient\'s lower back was prepped and draped in the usual sterile fashion.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 10pt\"><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\">Transverse process of and has been identified in an anterior posterior view on the camera. The camera was tilted to almost 30 degrees and inferior superior articular process of ---------------, ------------------, and has been identified. Subcutaneous 1%</span><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\">.</span><span style=\"line-height: 115%; font-size: 12pt\">Lidocaine was instilled into the superficial soft tissue of the patient\'s lower back for local anesthesia. A #22 gauge 3.5 inch spinal needle was advanced along the superior margin of the transverse process and lateral to the superior articular process and it was then directed inferiorly and medially so that the tip stuck the junction of the base of the transverse process and superior articular process of the target vertebrae. The needle was then walked over the superior aspect of the transverse process and advanced about 2 mm along the course of the respective medical branch nerve. At this location, 3 ml of 0.5% preservative free bupivacaine was injected along with 20 mg kenalog. Before the injection, it was made sure that the needle is in contact with the bone and the aspiration was negative for blood, CSF, or any other body fluid. The needle was then removed. The similar procedure was repeated to block all other levels. The patient tolerated the procedure very well and there was no complication observed during or immediately after the procedure. The patient was transferred to the recovery room in stable condition and was discharged home with appropriate instructions.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"margin: 0in 0in 10pt\">&nbsp;</div>',378,0,0),
(140,'Lumbar Sympathetic Block (Qadeer, Masoom)','<p>History and physical examination was reviewed. Risks, benefits and alternatives to the procedure has been discussed with the patienty. All questions were answered up to the patient\'s satisfaction. All informed voluntary consent was taken from the patient. Intravenous line was secured. The patient was taken to the operating room and was placed prone on the fluoroscopy table.Regular operating room monitors were placed by anesthesiologist and the lower back areas were prepped and draped with regular sterile fashion.</p>\r\n<p>L2-Ls transverse process has been identified on the right/left side. Skin wheal was made at 7 cm lateral to the spinous process of L2 and L on the right/left side. With spinal needle perpendicular to the skin, a track of local anesthestic was infiltrated down the transverse process at each level. The sympathectomy needle is then direcgted to the same point and the depth was noted after the needle was withdrawn to the subcutaneus tissue. The needle was then redirected so as to pass below and slightly medial to the inferior border of the transverse process at an angle of about 10 degrees to the sagittal plane. It was then advanced about 2cm deep to the transverse process to come in contact with the side of the vertebral body. A slight degree in the angle was amde so as to aqllow the needle to sloop past at a tangent to the l;ateral aspect of the vertebral body. A 2cc of Omnipasque 180 was injected through each needle to observe the spread of the contrast medium over each vertebral body. After negative aspiration of blood, CSF, or any other fluid, _____cc of 1/4% bupivacaine and _____mg of Kenalog was injected through each needle. The needle was withdrawn. The back was cleaned and a sterile band aid was applied. The patient remianed hemodynamically stable throughout the procedure. There was no complaints of parathesia and local anesthetic toxicilty was observed. The patient was then transferred to the recovery room in stable condition and was dischaarged home after adequate observation. The patient was given all the postoperative instructions.</p>\r\n<p>sincercerly,</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>MAsoom Qadeer, MD</p>',378,0,0),
(141,'Cataract','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<div>PROCEDURE: The operative eye was marked by the surgeon, prior to prepping by the circulating nurse. The patient was brought to the operating room in good condition. Topical anesthetic was applied. The patient was prepped and draped in the usual manner.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>A lid speculum was inserted. The surgical operating microscope with coaxial illumination was used for the entirety of the surgical procedure with the assistant microscope attachment. Peripheral corneal paracentesis incisions were made using a 75 Beaver or &laquo;similar blade at 2 hours clockwise from the primary incision location. &laquo;Preservative free Xylocaine 1% was injected into the anterior chamber for intraocular anesthesia. A keratome was used to enter the anterior chamber beginning at the limbus and creating a clear corneal tunnel in the process. Viscoelastic was instilled in the anterior chamber. A bent tipped #25 gauge needle was used to initiate an anteriorCapsulotomy. Forceps were used to perform a circular capsulorhexis. Hydrodissection and cortical cleavage, followed by viscodissection were performed.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>The ultrasonic handpiece was then introduced through the incision and used to emulsify and aspirate the entire nucleus within the posterior chamber. During the phaco-emulsification procedure, a Mackool chopper was inserted through the corneal incision in order to position, fracture, chop, and/or rotate the nucleus and continuously maintain its location away from the corneal endothelium at all times.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>Following completion of phacoemulsification, the irrigation/aspiration handpiece was used to remove all remaining lens cortex.The lid speculum and sterile drapes were removed. The operating room table was returned to the upright (chair) position, and the patient remained seated for a short time in order to avoid any postural circulatory disturbance.</div>\r\n\r\n<div>The patient tolerated the procedure well, and was escorred to the recovery room in good condition, then discharged from the ASC.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n',378,0,0),
