(151,'PPV Membrane Peel','<p>\r\n	The patient was brought to the operating room, correctly identifying her as Donna Nash, and she was placed under anesthesia. After the induction of anesthesia, the patient&rsquo;s right eye was prepped and draped in the usual manner for sterile intraocular surgery. Once a time out was taken to ensure that the right eye was the operative site surgery commenced. Barraquer wire lids had been placed under the lids of the right eye and a standard 25 gauge trocar system was placed with the infusion cannula being placed 4 mm posterior to the limbus inferotemporally and 2 superior sclerotomies created approximately at the 10 and 2 position, 4 mm posterior to the limbus n this phakic eye. A significant amount of vitreous hemorrhage was noted and there was no view whatsoever to the posterior pole. Vitrectomy was performed and a core vitrectomy allowed me to visualize the retina. There was traction nasally which was delaminated without difficulty using only the INNOVIT handpiece. The vitreous was segmented to the periphery as completely as possible in this phakic eye. There was vitreous and hemorrhage layered on the posterior surface of the lens. I was able to remove the vitreous. Though a cataract was forming, I was able to complete the vitrectomy and remove as much as the peripheral vitreous skirt as I could in this phakic eye. The blood was vacuumed off the surface of the retina and using both indirect laser and endolaser a total of 1397 pulses of laser were applied to this eye which had previous panretinal photocoagulation. Inspection revealed the retina to be flat and attached; no breaks or tears were noted. The trocar system was then removed and each of the sclerotomies were tested and found to be watertight. Subconjunctival injection of antibiotic and steroid was placed. Topical atropine was placed on the eye. Inspection revealed the retina to be flat and attached with no breaks, tears, holes or subretinal fluid. The eye was then patched and shielded. The patient was extubated and taken to the recovery room in stable condition. DISCHARGE SUMMARY: The patient was discharged to home status post trans pars plana vitrectomy with endolaser photocoagulation. The procedures and recovery were tolerated well<span style=\"display: none\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n',380,0,0),
(142,'Cataract','<p>PATIENT: {PATIENT FIRST NAME} {MIDDLE INITIAL} {LAST NAME}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DATE: {DATE}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PRE-OPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Visually significant cataract {SITE}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>POST-OPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Same</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SURGEON: {SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PROCEDURE: {PROCEDURE}, {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}{SITE}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OPERATION: The patient was brought into the OR after IV sedation and peri-bulbar block by the anesthesiologist. After attachment of appropriate monitoring equipment, the patient was prepped and draped in a sterile manner. A lid speculum was inserted. A fornix based conjunctival flap was fashioned with .12mm forceps and Wescott scissors. Hemostasis was achieved with bipolar cautery. A scleral incision was created with a keratome. The anterior chamber was reformed with viscoelastic agent. A paracentesis was created. A continuous curvilinear capsulorhexis was fashioned with a cystotome and capsulorhexis forceps. BSS was irrigated under the capsular rim and a posterior fluid wave was noted. The nucleus was rotated with the irrigating tip. Hydrodelineation was effected using the irrigating tip. Phacoemulsification was then performed in a &#39;stop and chop&#39; manner. Phacoemulsification time: ______. Aspiration of cortical material was effected with the Simcoe I/A unit. At the conclusion of this, the posterior capsule was noted to be intact. The capsular bag was reinflated with viscoelastic agent. A posterior chamber intra-ocular lens was inserted into the capsular bag. The viscoelastic agent was removed with the Simcoe unit. The anterior chamber was reformed with BSS. The incision was dried, tested for leakage and found to exhibit none. The conjunctival flap was reapproximated with jeweler tip cautery. Antibiotic ointment was applied to the eye. The operative drapes and speculum were removed and the eye was closed and covered with a sterile dressing and eye shield. The patient left the operating room in a stable condition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Post-Operative Plan - See patient postoperatively 24 hours after surgery. Patient to receive postoperative instructions for care and precautions of the eye from the surgery center which were adopted by the medical staff of Surgisite Boston. A copy of these instructions is maintained in the policy and procedure manual of Surgisite Boston.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>{SURGEON NAME}, M.D.</p>\r\n',380,0,0),
(143,'Complex Cataract','<p>Procedure: {PROCEDURE} {SITE}</p>\r\n<p>Secondary procedure: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE} {SITE}</p>\r\n<p>Pre-op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</p>\r\n<p>Post-op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</p>\r\n<p>FINDINGS/PROCEDURE:</p>\r\n<p>Prior to going to the surgery, all risks, benefits and alternatives were discussed in detail with the</p>\r\n<p>patient. All questions were answered. Informed consent was obtained and placed in the medical</p>\r\n<p>record. The patient was brought to the operating room in stable condition and placed into the supine</p>\r\n<p>position. Following mild sedation, the anesthesiologist administered a peribulbar anesthetic block. The</p>\r\n<p>operated was then prepped and draped in the usual sterile fashion.</p>\r\n<p>A sterile lid speculum was inserted and removed at the end of the case. Superior paracentesis was</p>\r\n<p>created, followed by injection of Viscoat to inflate the anterior chamber. A clear corneal incision</p>\r\n<p>was made temporally with a 2.4-mm keratome in a biplanar fashion. A cystotome was used to start</p>\r\n<p>a continuous circular capsulorrhexis, which was finished using Utrata forceps. BSS was used to</p>\r\n<p>hydrodissect the lens nucleus away from capsular bag. Complete nucleus mobility was achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Phacoemulsification probe and a chopper were used in concert to divide the lens nucleus into smaller</p>\r\n<p>pieces, which were then removed without difficulties.</p>\r\n<p>Next, irrigation and aspiration handpiece was used to clean up the capsular bag from cortical material.</p>\r\n<p>The capsular bag was re-inflated with Provisc and a single-piece foldable lens implant (SN60WF) was</p>\r\n<p>then injected into the capsular bag without incident. The lens implant was seen to be in good position</p>\r\n<p>and well centered. Viscoelastic device was removed with the IA probe. Intracameral vancomycin was</p>\r\n<p>injected. The incisions were then stromally hydrated with BSS. All wounds were checked for leaks</p>\r\n<p>and none were noted. Intraocular pressure was brought to physiologic level. The eye was then dressed</p>\r\n<p>with vigamox and prednisolone acetate 1% drops, patched and shielded. The patient tolerated the</p>\r\n<p>procedure well and was transferred to the recovery room in excellent condition.</p>',310,0,0),
(144,'CAT','<p><font size=\"3\"><b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">Procedure:</span></b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"> {PROCEDURE} {SITE}<o:p></o:p></span></font></p>\r\n<p><font size=\"3\"><b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">Secondary procedure:</span></b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"> {SECONDARY PROCEDURE} None</span></font></p>\r\n<p><font size=\"3\"><b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">Pre-op Diagnosis:</span></b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"> {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}<o:p></o:p></span></font></p>\r\n<p><font size=\"3\"><b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\">Post-op Diagnosis:</span></b><span style=\"font-family: Arial\"> {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</span></font></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-size: small\">PROCEDURE:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: small\"> The operative eye was marked by the surgeon, prior to prepping by the circulating nurse. The patient was brought to the operating room and placed supine on the operating table. Topical anesthetic was applied. The patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.</span> <span style=\"font-size: small\">A lid speculum was inserted. The surgical operating microscope with coaxial illumination was used for the entirety of the surgical procedure with the assistant microscope attachment. Peripheral corneal paracentesis incisions were made using a 75 Beaver or similar blade at 2 o\'clock hours clockwise from the primary incision location. Preservative free Xylocaine 1% was injected into the anterior chamber for intraocular anesthesia. A keratome was used to enter the anterior chamber beginning at the limbus and creating a clear corneal tunnel in the process. Viscoelastic was instilled in the anterior chamber. A bent tipped #25 gauge needle was used to initiate an anterior capsulotomy. Forceps were used to perform a circular capsulorhexis. Hydrodissection and cortical cleavage, followed by viscodissection were performed.</span><span style=\"font-size: small\">The ultrasonic hand-piece was then introduced through the incision and used to emulsify and aspirate the entire nucleus within the posterior chamber. During the phaco-emulsification procedure, a Mackool chopper was inserted through the corneal incision in order to position, fracture, chop, and/or rotate the nucleus and continuously maintain its location away from the corneal endothelium at all times.</span></p>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-size: small\">Following completion of phacoemulsification, the irrigation/ aspiration hand-piece was used to remove all remaining lens cortex. Viscoelastic was injected into the anterior chamber and the capsular sac was polished. Viscoelastic was then irrigated and/or aspirated from the anterior chamber. The globe was inflated with BSS and the incisions were hydrated and noted to be watertight. 0.1cc Vancomycin solution was injected into anterior chamber. The lid speculum and sterile drapes were removed. The operating room table was returned to the upright (chair) position, and the patient remained seated for a short time in order to avoid any postural circulatory disturbance. The patient tolerated the procedure well, and was escorted to the recovery room in good condition.</span></div>\r\n</div>',384,0,0),
(145,'CAT VIT','<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong><span>Procedure:</span></strong><span> {PROCEDURE} <strong>{SITE}</strong></span></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong><span>Secondary procedure:</span></strong><span> {SECONDARY PROCEDURE} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong><span>Pre-op Diagnosis:</span></strong><span> {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS} </span><strong><span>{SITE}</span></strong></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong><span>Post-op Diagnosis:</span></strong><span> {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong><span><span><span>PROCEDURE:</span></span></span></strong>The operative eye was marked by the surgeon, prior to prepping by the circulating nurse. The patient was brought to the operating room and placed supine on the operating table. Topical anesthetic was applied. The patient was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner. A lid speculum was inserted. The surgical operating microscope with coaxial illumination was used for the entirety of the surgical procedure with the assistant microscope attachment. Peripheral corneal paracentesis incisions were made using a 75 Beaver or similar blade at 2 o&#39;clock hours clockwise from the primary incision location. Preservative free Xylocaine 1% was injected into the anterior chamber for intraocular anesthesia. A keratome was used to enter the anterior chamber beginning at the limbus and creating a clear corneal tunnel in the process. Viscoelastic was instilled in the anterior chamber. A bent tipped #25 gauge needle was used to initiate an anterior capsulotomy. Forceps were used to perform a circular capsulorhexis. Hydrodissection and cortical cleavage, followed by viscodissection were performed.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		The ultrasonic hand-piece was then introduced through the incision and used to emulsify and aspirate the entire nucleus within the posterior chamber. During the phaco-emulsification procedure, a Mackool chopper was inserted through the corneal incision in order to position, fracture, chop, and/or rotate the nucleus and continuously maintain its location away from the corneal endothelium at all times.</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		Following completion of phacoemulsification, the irrigation/ aspiration hand-piece was used to remove all remaining lens cortex.Viscoelastic was injected into the anterior chamber and the anterior chamber intraocular lens was inserted into the capsular sac. Contact of all instruments with the corneal endothelium was carefully avoided. The corneal wound was closed with 10-0 nylon. Viscoelastic was then irrigated and/or aspirated from the anterior chamber. The globe was inflated with BSS and other incisions were hydrated and noted to be watertight. 0.1cc Vancomycin solution was injected into anterior chamber. The lid speculum and sterile drapes were removed. The operating room table was returned to the upright (chair) position, and the patient remained seated for a short time in order to avoid any postural circulatory disturbance. The patient tolerated the procedure well, and was escorted to the recovery room in good condition.</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong>ADDENDUM ANTERIOR VITRECTOMY:</strong> Vitreous prolapse was noted during/after phacoemulsification. Incisions were performed at the corneal limbus for a chamber maintainer and vitrecomy tip. The vitrectomy tip was introduced and used to remove vitreous until none was noted in the anterior chamber. The wounds were hydrated and noted to be self sealing.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong>ADDENDUM POSTERIOR VITRECTOMY:</strong> Vitreous prolapse was noted during/after phacoemulsification. Incisions were performed at the corneal limbus for a chamber maintainer and 3.5 mm posterior to the sclera for a vitrecomy tip. The vitrectomy tip was introduced and used to remove vitreous until none was noted in the anterior chamber. The wounds were hydrated and noted to be self sealing.</div>\r\n',384,0,0),
