y maintain its location away from the corneal endothelium at all times.</div>\r\n<div>Following completion of phacoemulsification, the irrigation/ aspiration hand-piece was used to remove all remaining lens cortex.Viscoelastic was injected into the anterior chamber and the anterior chamber intraocular lens was inserted into the capsular sac. Contact of all instruments with the corneal endothelium was carefully avoided. The corneal wound was closed with 10-0 nylon. Viscoelastic was then irrigated and/or aspirated from the anterior chamber. The globe was inflated with BSS and other incisions were hydrated and noted to be watertight. 0.1cc Vancomycin solution was injected into anterior chamber. The lid speculum and sterile drapes were removed. The operating room table was returned to the upright (chair) position, and the patient remained seated for a short time in order to avoid any postural circulatory disturbance. The patient tolerated the procedure well, and was escorted to the recovery room in good condition.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div><strong>ADDENDUM ANTERIOR VITRECTOMY:</strong> Vitreous prolapse was noted during/after phacoemulsification. Incisions were performed at the corneal limbus for a chamber maintainer and vitrecomy tip. The vitrectomy tip was introduced and used to remove vitreous until none was noted in the anterior chamber. The wounds were hydrated and noted to be self sealing.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>ADDENDUM POSTERIOR VITRECTOMY:</strong> Vitreous prolapse was noted during/after phacoemulsification. Incisions were performed at the corneal limbus for a chamber maintainer and 3.5 mm posterior to the sclera for a vitrecomy tip. The vitrectomy tip was introduced and used to remove vitreous until none was noted in the anterior chamber. The wounds were hydrated and noted to be self sealing.</div>',310,0,0),
(147,'Cat W/ IOL','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div><span>Procedure: {PROCEDURE} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div><span>Secondary procedure: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>Pre-op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>Post-op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>PROCEDURE:</strong> The operative eye was marked by the surgeon, prior to prepping by the circulating nurse. The patient was brought to the operating room in good condition. Topical anesthetic was applied. The patient was prepped and draped in the usual manner.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>A lid speculum was inserted. The surgical operating microscope with coaxial illumination was used for the entirety of the surgical procedure with the assistant microscope attachment. Peripheral corneal paracentesis incisions were made using a 75 Beaver or &laquo;similar blade at 2 hours clockwise from the primary incision location. &laquo;Preservative free Xylocaine 1% was injected into the anterior chamber for intraocular anesthesia. A keratome was used to enter the anterior chamber beginning at the limbus and creating a clear corneal tunnel in the process. Viscoelastic was instilled in the anterior chamber. A bent tipped #25 gauge needle was used to initiate an anteriorCapsulotomy. Forceps were used to perform a circular capsulorhexis. Hydrodissection and cortical cleavage, followed by viscodissection were performed.\r\n<div>The ultrasonic hand-piece was then introduced through the incision and used to emulsify and aspirate the entire nucleus within the posterior chamber. During the phaco-emulsification procedure, a Mackool chopper was inserted through the corneal incision in order to position, fracture, chop, and/or rotate the nucleus and continuously maintain its location away from the corneal endothelium at all times. Following completion of phacoemulsification, the irrigation/aspiration hand-piece was used to remove all remaining lens cortex. The lid speculum and sterile drapes were removed. The operating room table was returned to the upright (chair) position, and the patient remained seated for a short time in order to avoid any postural circulatory disturbance. The patient tolerated the procedure well, and was escorted to the recovery room in good condition, then discharged from the ASC.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><span>Richard J. Mackool, M.D.</span></div>\r\n</div>',379,0,0),
(148,'PPV','<p>\r\n	&nbsp;FINDINGS/PROCEDURE: After ensuring that informed consent was obtained the patient was properly identified, laid on the operating room table in the supine position. Intravenous sedation was administered by the anesthesiologist after a retrobulbar block consisting of 50:50 mixture of 2% lidocaine and 0.75% Sensorcaine totaling approximately 5 cc was administered to the periorbital space. The operative eye was then prepped and draped in the usual sterile ophthalmologic fashion. A lid speculum was placed in the operative eye. Three 25-gauge cannulas were placed 4 millimeters posterior to the limbus in the superonasal, superotemporal and inferotemporal space. A pars plana vitrectomy was performed. Inspection of the intraocular lens noted that it was dislocated nasally. A paracentesis was made in the inferotemporal and superotemporal limbus. Healon was injected into the anterior chamber. The lens was carefully moved from the nasal aspect of the sulcus temporally. It was noted that both haptics were still captured by the iris and were felt to be holding the haptics. It was believed that the superior haptic needed to be fixated more securely. The lens was recentered. A paracentesis was made at the superotemporal limbus with a diamond blade. A 10-0 Prolene suture was then used to fix the superior haptic to the iris securely. The sutures were tied. Before this was done Miochol was injected into the anterior chamber to bring the optic into the anterior chamber. After this was completed the optic was then placed back into the posterior chamber. Balanced salt solution was used to irrigate the anterior chamber to see if the intraocular lens decentered. It was found to be secured. A pars plana vitrectomy was then again performed to remove any cortical debris that existed more temporally. The instruments were removed. The sclerotomies were closed with pressure. The paracentesis inferotemporally was closed with 10-0 nylon suture. The wounds were checked and were all found to be secure. The lid speculum was removed and the drapes were removed. The patient was taken back to the operating room after tolerating the procedure well. DISCHARGE SUMMARY: The patient was discharged to home status post pars plana vitrectomy with refixating of iris fixated intraocular lens. The procedures and recovery were tolerated well. Patient will be seen in the office for follow up.</p>\r\n',380,0,0),
(152,'Vision Blue with hooks','<p>\r\n	Procedure: 1. Cataract Extraction with Intraocular Lens Implant Left Eye. 2. Vision Blue used for anterior capsule visualization. 3. Posterior synechiae release and iris hook placement for pupil dilation. Pre-op diagnosis: Mature Cataract Left Eye and posterior synechiae. Post-op diagnosis: Mature Cataract Left Eye and posterior synechiae. Blood Loss: Less than 5cc Complications: None Anesthesia: Monitored Anesthesia Care and Peribulbar Block Procedure: The patient was identified and the anesthesiologist administered&nbsp; a&nbsp;peribulbar block.&nbsp;The patient was then brought into the operating room placed on the operative table in the supine position. The patient was prepped and draped in the usual&nbsp;sterile ophthalmic fashion. A Lieberman speculum was&nbsp;placed to open the eyelids. A stab incision was made using the side port blade. Air was injected into the anterior chamber using a&nbsp;3cc syringe on a blunt cannula. Then Vision Blue was injected into the anterior chamber also using a 3cc syringe on a blunt cannula. Viscoelastic material was then injected into the anterior chamber. A spatula and kuglan hook was used to release the posterior synechiae. Four iris hooks were then placed for pupillary dilation. The anterior was opened&nbsp;using the 2.4mm Keratome blade. A continuous curvilinear capsularhexis was made using the cytosome and utratta forceps. Balanced&nbsp;Salt Solution (BSS)&nbsp;was injected underneath the capsule to perform hydro-dissection and hydro delineation. Phacoemulsification then proceeded removing most of the nuclear&nbsp;and cortical material. The I/A hand piece was then&nbsp;used to remove the remainder of the cortical material.&nbsp;Viscoelastic was injected to fill the capsular bag. A foldable intraocular lens was then injected into the capsular bag and centered with a Sinskey hook. The viscoelastic material was then removed from the anterior chamber with the I/A hand piece. At the end of the case, the corneal wounds were hydrated with BSS on a blunt-tipped cannula. The iris hooks were removed. The wounds were tested and found to be water tight. The Lieberman speculum was carefully removed. Besivance and Pred Forte 1% were then placed in the eye. An eye shield was then used to cover the eye. There were no complications. The patient tolerated the procedure well and was transferred from the operating room in stable condition.</p>\r\n',384,0,0),
(153,'cataract with IOL','<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>\r\n	<span>Procedure: {PROCEDURE} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<span>Secondary procedure: {SECONDARY PROCEDURE} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<span>Pre-op Diagnosis: {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<span>Post-op Diagnosis: {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</span></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong>PROCEDURE:</strong> The operative eye was marked by the surgeon, prior to prepping by the circulating nurse. The patient was brought to the operating room in good condition. Topical anesthetic was applied. The patient was prepped and draped in the usual manner.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	A lid speculum was inserted. The surgical operating microscope with coaxial illumination was used for the entirety of the surgical procedure with the assistant microscope attachment. Peripheral corneal paracentesis incisions were made using a 75 Beaver or &laquo;similar blade at 2 hours clockwise from the primary incision location. &laquo;Preservative free Xylocaine 1% was injected into the anterior chamber for intraocular anesthesia. A keratome was used to enter the anterior chamber beginning at the limbus and creating a clear corneal tunnel in the process. Viscoelastic was instilled in the anterior chamber. A bent tipped #25 gauge needle was used to initiate an anteriorCapsulotomy. Forceps were used to perform a circular capsulorhexis. Hydrodissection and cortical cleavage, followed by viscodissection were performed.\r\n	<div>\r\n		The ultrasonic hand-piece was then introduced through the incision and used to emulsify and aspirate the entire nucleus within the posterior chamber. During the phaco-emulsification procedure, a Mackool chopper was inserted through the corneal incision in order to position, fracture, chop, and/or rotate the nucleus and continuously maintain its location away from the corneal endothelium at all times. Following completion of phacoemulsification, the irrigation/aspiration hand-piece was used to remove all remaining lens cortex. The lid speculum and sterile drapes were removed. The operating room table was returned to the upright (chair) position, and the patient remained seated for a short time in order to avoid any postural circulatory disturbance. The patient tolerated the procedure well, and was escorted to the recovery room in good condition, then discharged from the ASC.</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		&nbsp;</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		<span>Richard J. Mackool, M.D.</span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n',384,0,0),
(154,'Blepharoplasty','<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\"><strong>ANESTHESIA:</strong>&nbsp; Local with sedation</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">PRE-OPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:&nbsp; {PRE - OP DIAGNOSIS}, {SITE} </span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">POST-OPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:&nbsp; {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}, {SITE}</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">OPERATION:&nbsp; </span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">{PROCEDURE}, {SITE}</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">FINDINGS/PROCEDURE:&nbsp; The patient was brought to the Operating Room after clearance was obtained from medical and anesthesia consults.&nbsp; The patient signed written consent after the risks, benefits and alternatives of the procedure were explained to the patient pre-operatively.&nbsp; The patient arrived in the Operating Room and was placed on the OR table in the supine position.&nbsp; Vital sign monitoring was begun by Anesthesia.&nbsp; An intravenous line was placed.&nbsp; The patient was intravenously sedated.</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">Each upper eyelid crease was demarcated with a Gentian violet marking pen from nasally to temporally.&nbsp; A second line of incision was drawn ___ mm superior to the first line superiorly centrally and tapering beneath the lower incision line nasally and temporally.&nbsp; Each upper eyelid was then injected with lidocaine 2% with 1:100,000 epinephrine for the full horizontal extent of the marked areas.&nbsp; The patient was sterilely prepped and draped for surgery.&nbsp; Corneal shields were placed in each palpebral fissure.</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">The upper eyelid incisions were then incised utilizing the premarked lines with a #15 blade and skin and orbicularis resected en block in elliptical fashion utilizing Westcott scissors and Adson forceps.&nbsp; Suborbicularis dissection was performed to expose the orbital septum which was buttonholed centrally and opened for the full horizontal extent of each incision.&nbsp; The pre-aponeurotic fat pads were identified centrally and medially and were gently debulked utilizing Colorado-tipped Bovie cautery with careful hemostasis throughout that portion of the procedure.&nbsp; When appropriate amounts of fat were debulked, the skin was then closed with a combination of running and interrupted 6-O nylon sutures.</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">The patient&#39;s face was then cleaned and dried with wet and dry sponges.&nbsp; The corneal shields were removed from each palpebral fissure.&nbsp; The wound and eye were coated with bacitracin ointment on each side.</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><span style=\"font-size: x-small;\">The patient was brought to the recovery area from the operating room, having tolerated the procedure well, in good condition without complication.</span></span></p>\r\n',384,0,0),
(155,'Phaco with Trab','<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><strong>Pre-Operative Diagnosis:&nbsp;</strong> {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS}, {SITE}</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><strong>Post-Operative Diagnosis:</strong> {POST-OP DIAGNOSIS}, {SITE}</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><strong>Operation:&nbsp;</strong> 1.&nbsp; {PROCEDURE}, {SITE}&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2.&nbsp; {SECONDARY PROCEDURE}, {SITE}</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"><strong>Findings/Procedure:&nbsp;</strong> After adequate anesthesia was achieved, the patient was transported to the operative suite where the eye was prepped and draped in the usual sterile surgical fashion.&nbsp; A lid speculum was placed in the eye.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">A 7-O Vicryl suture was placed through the superior clear cornea to place the eye in infraduction.&nbsp; A conjunctival peritomy was created from approximately the 10 o&#39;clock to 1 o&#39;clock meridians superiorly.&nbsp; This was dissected posteriorly in all directions in a fornix-based fashion.&nbsp; A dry scleral field was achieved with a hemostatic eraser.&nbsp; Two Pledgets of mitomycin C were then inserted subconjunctivally and left in place for a period of three minutes.&nbsp; The Pledgets were removed and the area was copiously irrigated with balanced salt solution.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">A crescent blade was then used to create a half-thickness scleral groove.&nbsp; This was undermined anteriorly into clear cornea.&nbsp; A Vannas scissor was then used to convert this scleral tunnel into a half-thickness scleral flap.&nbsp; A paracentesis was then created in the 1:30 o &#39;clock meridian.&nbsp; Viscoat was injected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A 2.75 mm keratome was then used to enter the anterior chamber beneath the scleral flap.&nbsp; Provisc was injuected into the anterior chamber.&nbsp; A continuous curvilinear capsulorrhexis was created with a cystotome and Utrata forceps.&nbsp; Hydrodissection was performed with balanced salt solution on a Change cannula.&nbsp; The lens was emulsified and aspirated using a four-quadrant divide-and-conquer technique.&nbsp; Remaining cortical material was then removed using the irrigation and aspiration handpiece.&nbsp; Provisc was injected into the apsular bag to deepen it.&nbsp; A intraocular lens was injected into the capsular bag and noted to be in good position.&nbsp; Two 10-O nylon sutures were then pre-placed through the previously-created scleral flap.&nbsp; The remaining viscoelastic materal was then removed from the eye.&nbsp; A Kelly punch was used to create a sclerotomy beneath the scleral flap.&nbsp; A iridectomy was performed with a Vannas scissor and Jeweler forcep.&nbsp; The pre-placed 10-O nylon sutures were closed to an appropriate tension to adjust for flow through the trabeculectomy.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Attention was then turned to conjunctival closure.&nbsp; Three interrupted 10-O nylon mattress sutures were used to close the conjunctiva in a watertight fashion.&nbsp; An additional 10-O nylon suture was used to close the paracentesis port.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Good bleb formation was noted at the conclusion of the case and watertight closure was confirmed with fluorescein dye.&nbsp; A subconjunctival injection of dexamethasone and Ancef was given at the conclusion of the case.&nbsp; The lid speculum and drapes were removed.&nbsp; The patient was transported to the Post Anesthesia CAre Unit in stable condition having tolerated the procedure well.&nbsp; There were no complications.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">The paitent received post-operative instructions and an appointment to follow up in the office the following day.</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">{SURGEON NAME} , MD</span></p>\r\n',384,0,0),
(159,'Chalazion','<p>\r\n	<strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Procedure:&nbsp; </span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">{PROCEDURE} {SITE}</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Pre-op diagnosis:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\"> {PRE-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Post-op diagnosis:&nbsp; </span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">{POST-OP DIAGNOSIS} {SITE}</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Blood Loss:&nbsp; Less than 5cc</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Complications:&nbsp; None</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Anesthesia:&nbsp; Monitored Anesthesia Care and&nbsp;Local Anesthesia</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Procedure:</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">&nbsp;The patient was identified and brought into the operating room placed on the operative table in the supine position.&nbsp; The affected eye was prepped and draped in the usual ophthalmic sterile fashion.&nbsp; Approximately 3cc of 2% Lidocaine with Epinephrine was injected around the chalazion for anesthesia and hemostasis.&nbsp; A chalazion clamp was placed over the lesion.&nbsp; The eyelid was everted.&nbsp; Using the 11-blade a incision was made entering the chalazion.&nbsp; The contents were excised using a combination of a curette, Wescott scissor and 0.3 forcep.&nbsp; Using the curette the edge was also cleaned.&nbsp; A hot temperature cautery was used to cauterize the edges of the wound.&nbsp; The chalazion clamp was then carefully removed and Tobradex ointment was placed into the eye.&nbsp; A pressure patch was placed over the eye.&nbsp; The patient tolerated the procedure well and was sent to the recovery area in satisfactory condition.</span></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">{Surgeon Name}, MD</span></span></p>\r\n',384,0,0),
(158,'Pterygium','<p>\r\n	Patient was taken from the preoperative area to the Operating Room and placed in the supine position. A time-out was taken and surgery was verified. Patient was then prepped and draped in the usual sterile fashion for ocular plastic surgery. A skin marker was then used to delineate the left upper lid crease along its lateral border. This was also done on the right upper lid. Green&rsquo;s forceps were then used to grasp the tissue superior to the lid crease. The appropriate amount was grasped for planned removal. This area was then marked along the superior edge. The inner aspects of the markings were then joined and the lateral aspects of the markings were also joined. Close attention was paid to insure that no lagophthalmos was created. At this point, lidocaine 2.0% with epinephrine was then injected locally under the premarked skin area, on the left upper lid as well as the right upper lid. Cool compresses were placed on the lids. Attention was first paid to the left side where a #15 blade was then used to incise the skin along the area that was premarked. The skin was then initially removed using Westcott, and 0.12 and then with a Bovie. Hemostasis was achieved using the Bovie cautery as well. Then 6-0 Prolene suture was then used to close the incision with a running subcuticular stitch pattern. The ends were bolstered with small pieces of rubber band and tied to the Prolene suture. The wound was noted to be well approximated. No lagophthalmos was appreciated. The same technique was performed on the right upper lid with no lagophthalmos appreciated as well. Maxitrol and cold compresses were placed. Patient tolerated the procedure without any complications. Patient was instructed to take oral antibiotics and Topical TobraDex and follow up in one week with Dr. Richard in the eye clinic.</p>\r\n',384,0,0),
